idth=30em|refs=\n}}\n\n===Notes===\n* Production code information can be found at the following links:\n** {{Cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/pig-goat-banana-cricket/listings/|title=Shows A\u2013Z&nbsp;\u2013 ''Pig Goat Banana Cricket'' on Nickelodeon|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|accessdate=6 February 2016}}\n** {{Cite web|url=http://www.rogersondemand.com/OnDemand/Show/pig_goat_banana_cricket?lang=en|title=''Pig Goat Banana Cricket'' Season 1|publisher=[[Rogers Cable]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206134946/http://www.rogersondemand.com/OnDemand/Show/pig_goat_banana_cricket?lang=en|archive-date=February 6, 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pig Goat Banana Cricket Episodes, List Of}}\n[[Category:Lists of American children's animated television series episodes]]\n[[Category:Nickelodeon-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of Nickelodeon television series episodes]]\n", "name_user": "202.93.153.226", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Pig_Goat_Banana_Cricket_episodes"}
{"title_page": "The Reprieve (1913 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n  | name     = The Reprieve\n  | image    = \n  | caption  = \n  | director = [[W. J. Lincoln]]\t\t\n  | producer = [[W. J. Lincoln]]<br>[[Godfrey Cass]]\n  | writer   = W. J. Lincoln<ref>[http://recordsearch.naa.gov.au/SearchNRetrieve/Interface/DetailsReports/ItemDetail.aspx?Barcode=202254 Copyright information for film] at [[National Archives of Australia]]</ref>\n  | starring = The Lincoln Cass Famous Picture Artists\n  | music    = \n  | cinematography = [[Maurice Bertel]]\n  | editing  = \n  | studio = [[Lincoln-Cass Films]]\n  | released = 3 November 1913 (Melbourne)<ref>Mary Bateman, 'Lincoln Cass Filmography', ''Cinema Papers'', June\u2013July 1980 p 175</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article196227358 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=18,291 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=1 November 1913 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n  | runtime  = 2,500 feet<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article61623015 |title=Picture Pops. |newspaper=[[Clarence and Richmond Examiner]] |location=Grafton, NSW |date=13 January 1914 |accessdate=14 April 2012 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> or 4,000 feet<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article123182022 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Maitland Daily Mercury]] |issue=13,370 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 January 1914 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n  | language = [[Silent film]]<br>English intertitles\n  | country = Australia\n  | budget   = \n  }}\n\n'''''The Reprieve''''' is a 1913 Australian melodrama film directed by [[W. J. Lincoln]] about a man on trial for killing his unfaithful wife. It is considered a [[lost film]]. Contemporary reviews were positive.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79909663 |title=SHAFTSBURY THEATRE. |newspaper=[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News]] |location=Perth |date=12 December 1914 |accessdate=14 April 2012 |page=6 Edition: THIRD EDITION |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nRichard Gannon discovers his wife Amy has been cheating on him with a man called Jim Williams and accidentally kills her in a fit of anger by pushing her over a cliff. He is arrested and sentenced to death but the judge recommends mercy and asks the Home Secretary for a reprieve.\n\nThe Home Secretary at first refuses, but when he mistakenly comes to believe that his own wife is unfaithful with a former lover, he realises how easy it would have been to kill her.\n\nAfter this, he grants a reprieve for Gannon and resolves to show his wife more affection.<ref>Andrew Pike and Ross Cooper, ''Australian Film 1900\u20131977: A Guide to Feature Film Production'', Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1998, p45</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article53371107 |title=Advertising. |newspaper=[[The Morning Bulletin]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=15 July 1915 |accessdate=14 April 2012 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article123200830 |title=GARDEN PICTURE PALACE. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Daily Mercury]] |issue=13,372 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 January 1914 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe chapter headings were:<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article107477785 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Tamworth Daily Observer]] |volume=IV |issue=20 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=24 January 1914 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Condemned to Death. \n*The Power of Love. \n*Leave my House, you Scoundrel.\n*Should a faithless woman be destroyed.\n*I have killed Her. \n*The Vigil of the Night.\n*A story that will hold you spell-bound.\n*You are no better than Richard Gannon, the man you refuse to reprieve.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Roy Redgrave]]\n*Beryl Bryant\n*[[Godfrey Cass]]\n*[[George Bryant (actor)|George Bryant]]\n*Tom Cannam<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137960181 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |issue=12,221 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=2 January 1914 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Violet Grey\n*Ward Lyons\n*Charles Wheeler\n*John Brunton\n*Jessie Brown\n\n==Production==\nThe film was the fifth production from Lincoln Cass.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article165146363 |title=MOVING PICTURES. |newspaper=[[The Prahran Telegraph]] |volume=51 |issue=2709 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=20 September 1913 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0193461/ ''The Reprieve''] at [[IMDb]]\n*[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/7609590 ''The Reprieve''] at [[AustLit]]\n*[http://colsearch.nfsa.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=no;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=%22the%20reprieve%22;querytype=;rec=4;resCount=10 ''The Reprieve''] at [[National Film and Sound Archive]]\n\n{{W.J. Lincoln}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reprieve}}\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:Australian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Australian silent feature films]]\n[[Category:1913 films]]\n[[Category:Lost Australian films]]\n[[Category:Australian drama films]]\n[[Category:1910s drama films]]\n[[Category:Melodramas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n  | name     = The Reprieve\n  | image    = \n  | caption  = \n  | director = [[W. J. Lincoln]]\t\t\n  | producer = [[W. J. Lincoln]]<br>[[Godfrey Cass]]\n  | writer   = W. J. Lincoln<ref>[http://recordsearch.naa.gov.au/SearchNRetrieve/Interface/DetailsReports/ItemDetail.aspx?Barcode=202254 Copyright information for film] at [[National Archives of Australia]]</ref>\n  | starring = The Lincoln Cass Famous Picture Artists\n  | music    = \n  | cinematography = [[Maurice Bertel]]\n  | editing  = \n  | studio = [[Lincoln-Cass Films]]\n  | released = 3 November 1913 (Melbourne)<ref>Mary Bateman, 'Lincoln Cass Filmography', ''Cinema Papers'', June\u2013July 1980 p 175</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article196227358 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=18,291 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=1 November 1913 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n  | runtime  = 2,500 feet<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article61623015 |title=Picture Pops. |newspaper=[[Clarence and Richmond Examiner]] |location=Grafton, NSW |date=13 January 1914 |accessdate=14 April 2012 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> or 4,000 feet<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article123182022 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Maitland Daily Mercury]] |issue=13,370 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 January 1914 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n  | language = [[Silent film]]<br>English intertitles\n  | country = Australia\n  | budget   = \n  }}\n\n'''''The Reprieve''''' is a 1913 Australian melodrama film directed by [[W. J. Lincoln]] about a man on trial for killing his unfaithful wife. It is considered a [[lost film]]. Contemporary reviews were positive.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article79909663 |title=SHAFTSBURY THEATRE. |newspaper=[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News]] |location=Perth |date=12 December 1914 |accessdate=14 April 2012 |page=6 Edition: THIRD EDITION |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nRichard Gannon discovers his wife Amy has been cheating on him with a man called Jim Williams and accidentally kills her in a fit of anger by pushing her over a cliff. He is arrested and sentenced to death but the judge recommends mercy and asks the Home Secretary for a reprieve.\n\nThe Home Secretary at first refuses, but when he mistakenly comes to believe that his own wife is unfaithful with a former lover, he realises how easy it would have been to kill her.\n\nAfter this, he grants a reprieve for Gannon and resolves to show his wife more affection.<ref>Andrew Pike and Ross Cooper, ''Australian Film 1900\u20131977: A Guide to Feature Film Production'', Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1998, p45</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article53371107 |title=Advertising. |newspaper=[[The Morning Bulletin]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=15 July 1915 |accessdate=14 April 2012 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article123200830 |title=GARDEN PICTURE PALACE. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Daily Mercury]] |issue=13,372 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 January 1914 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe chapter headings were:<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article107477785 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Tamworth Daily Observer]] |volume=IV |issue=20 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=24 January 1914 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Condemned to Death. \n*The Power of Love. \n*Leave my House, you Scoundrel.\n*Should a faithless woman be destroyed.\n*I have killed Her. \n*The Vigil of the Night.\n*A story that will hold you spell-bound.\n*You are no better than Richard Gannon, the man you refuse to reprieve.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Roy Redgrave]]\n*Beryl Bryant\n*[[Godfrey Cass]]\n*[[George Bryant (actor)|George Bryant]]\n*Tom Cannam<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137960181 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald And Miners' Advocate]] |issue=12,221 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=2 January 1914 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Violet Grey\n*Ward Lyons\n*Charles Wheeler\n*John Brunton\n*Jessie Brown\n\n==Production==\nThe film was the fifth production from Lincoln Cass.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article165146363 |title=MOVING PICTURES. |newspaper=[[The Prahran Telegraph]] |volume=51 |issue=2709 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=20 September 1913 |accessdate=2 May 2016 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0193461/ ''The Reprieve''] at [[IMDb]]\n*[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/7609590 ''The Reprieve''] at [[AustLit]]\n*[http://colsearch.nfsa.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=no;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=%22the%20reprieve%22;querytype=;rec=4;resCount=10 ''The Reprieve''] at [[National Film and Sound Archive]]\n\n{{W.J. Lincoln}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reprieve}}\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:Australian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Australian silent feature films]]\n[[Category:1913 films]]\n[[Category:Lost Australian films]]\n[[Category:Australian drama films]]\n[[Category:1910s drama films]]\n[[Category:Melodramas]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Reprieve_(1913_film)"}
{"title_page": "The Shadow of Lightning Ridge", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Shadow of Lightning Ridge\n| image          = Shadow_of_Lightning_Ridge.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| director       = [[Wilfred Lucas]]\n| producer       = [[E.J. Carroll]]<br>[[Snowy Baker]]\n| writer         = [[Bess Meredyth]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Snowy Baker]]<br>[[Agnes Vernon]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Robert Doerrer\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = Aywon Pictures (US)\n| studio          = Carroll-Baker Australian Productions\n| released       = 3 April 1920 (Australia)<br>13 September 1921 (US)\n| runtime        = 7 reels<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57918464 |title=\"SHADOW OF LIGHTNING RIDGE\" AT WEST'S. |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)|The Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=1 October 1920 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = [[Silent film]] <br>English intertitles\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n\n'''''The Shadow of Lightning Ridge''''' is a 1920 Australian [[silent film]] starring renowned Australian sportsman [[Snowy Baker]].<ref>{{Citation \n  | title=The Lone hand \n  | date=1907 \n  | publisher=W. McLeod \n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-393171672\n  | accessdate=4 June 2018\n}}</ref> It has been called the most \"Western\"-like of the films Baker made in Australia.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Filmink|first=Stephen|last=Vagg|title=50 Meat Pie Westerns|date=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt is now considered a [[lost film]].\n\n[[Charles Chauvel (filmmaker)|Charles Chauvel]] had a small role as a groom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article132858377 |title=TOPICS OF THE DAY |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |issue=21,972 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 March 1947 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110744601 |title=A RESOLUTE FILM MAKER |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=47 |issue=13,523 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=25 August 1973 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe success of the film prompted the formation of the Carroll-Baker Film Corporation with capital of \u00a325,000. A studio, Palmerston, at Waverly was established.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article222413479 |title=ALL AUSTRALIAN |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]] |issue=897 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 June 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nTravelling in a carriage is Sir Edward Marriott, a wealthy mine owner, his fianc\u00e9e Dorothy Hardyn, and a bag containing the month's pay for the miners. They are travelling to Marriott's estate at Lightning Ridge. There is also a man with a hacking cough.\n\nA conveyance with armed escort meets the train to prevent the large sum of money from a mysterious outlaw known as The Shadow. However The Shadow, the man with the hacking cough, gets the money and a necklace from the Dorothy. He jumps on to a horse and escapes.\n\nIt turns out the Shadow is actually a gentleman in disguise with a vendetta against Sir Edward because his mother has been victimised by him. He has become a The Shadow but only attacks Sir Edward's property.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article146689823 |title=THE SHADOW OF LIGHTNING RIDGE |newspaper=[[Table Talk (magazine)|Table Talk]] |issue=1810 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=1 April 1920 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe Shadow rescues Dorothy from real bushrangers and they fall in love. Later he discovers he is the real heir to Sir Edward's property. Portuguese Anne, who is in love with the Shadow, becomes jealous of Dorothy and arranges for the Shadow to be arrested. However he escapes.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57922010 \"WEST'S PICTURES.\" ''The Register (Adelaide)'' 28 Sep 1920: 6] accessed 18 December 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article138821985 |title=STRAND THEATRE. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |issue=14,216 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=1 June 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Snowy Baker]] as the Shadow\n*[[Agnes Vernon]] as Dorothy Harden\n*Bernice Vere as Portuguese Annie\n*[[Wilfred Lucas]] as Sir Edward Marriott\n*Evelyn Johnson<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120524924 |title=NEW AUSTRALIAN-MADE FILM |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Sydney)|The Sunday Times]] |issue=1790 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=16 May 1920 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Reg K Bisley as station guard<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-559440611|magazine=Everyone's|title=Along Film Row|date=22 April 1922|page=5}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe script was clearly inspired by [[Zorro]], which [[Bess Meredyth]] later adapted in ''[[The Mark of Zorro (1940 film)|The Mark of Zorro]]'' (1940). After reading the script and seeing the stunts he was required to perform, Baker reportedly went out and insured himself for \u00a35,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57922710 |title=AMUSEMENTS. |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)|The Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=30 September 1920 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nBernice Vere was a discovery of Baker's.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title=The bulletin\n  | date=1880\n  | publisher=John Haynes and J.F. Archibald\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-665875923\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref> She was signed to a 12-month contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article212993205 |title=[?] Baptist Association. |newspaper=[[Quorn Mercury]] |volume= |location=South Australia |date=10 September 1920 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nShooting took place in early 1920 in the bush near Sydney, at Bulli Pass and Loddon Falls<ref>{{Citation\n  | author1=Australian Geographical Society.\n  | author2=Australian National Publicity Association.\n  | author3=Australian National Travel Association.\n  | title=Walkabout\n  | date=1934\n  | publisher=Australian National Travel Association\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-751074193\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref> and at a studio built by [[E.J. Carroll]] at Palmerston near Waverly.<ref>[http://www.waverley.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/8739/PalmerstonStudio.pdf 'Palmerston Studio: Our pioneer silent film studio' Waverly Council]</ref>\n\nA highlight of the film was Snowy Baker on horseback jumping 40 metres off a cliff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57917030 |title=AUSTRALIAN-MADE FILMS. |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)|The Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=25 September 1920 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=10 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57922010 |title=WEST'S PICTURES. |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)|The Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=28 September 1920 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nBaker used a stuntman for some of the more dangerous scenes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article159028610 |title=NEWS OF THE FILM WORLD. |newspaper=[[Sydney Mail]] |volume=XVI |issue=415 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=10 March 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical===\nThe trade paper ''Everyone's'' said:\n<blockquote>Baker as an elusive bushranger brings joy to  the  hearts  of  the  Pussyfoots by entirely wrecking  a  bush pub.  Snowy  doesn\u2019t  do  it  on  behalf  of prohibition.  He\u2019s  escaping  from  the Law and the big  fight  that  ensues  causes the  damage.  It  was  thought  at  first that  the  big  scene  could  be  done  with empty  bottles  on  the  shelves,  but  so many  were  smashed  that  it  was  found that  there  was  a  sad  lack  of  realism. So,  to  the  horror  of  many  actors,  dozens of  bottles  of  real  whisky  were  deliberately  wasted.  Now,  it  is  said,  \"  The Shadow  of  Lightning  Ridge\"  is  certain of  a  tremendous  success  especially  after 6  p.m.  Thirsty  folk  will  go  along  just to  smell  the  bush  pubs  scene.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title=Everyones\n  | date=1920\n  | publisher=Everyones Ltd\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-536053965\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe ''Bulletin'' praised the photography but thought the story was too American saying the \"only Australian   thing   about\" the movie \"is   the   setting.  The   scenery   is   dinkum,   but   the   story   itself   is  a   mixture   of   old   melodrama   and   Wild   West  movie.   Australia   wants   Australian   films,   and  \nin   spite   of   \"Snowy\"   Baker's   great   athletic  business,   she   will   refuse   to   swallow   \"The  Shadow\"   as   the   thing   her   soul   cries   for.  \nLeading-woman   Brownie   Vernon,   also   being  American,   adds   nothing   Australian   to   the  picture.   But   the   photography   is   excellent.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine|magazine=The Bulletin|page=36|title=Sundry Shows|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-626908532|date=May 20, 1920}}</ref> Another article in the same magazine said the film \"claims   Australian   patronage   on   account   of  its   local   production,   but   is   in   all   its   gun play   and   other   effects   imitation   American.  Heaven   forbid   that   this   sort   of   stuff   should  go   out   to   the   world   as   dinkum   Australian   !\" <ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-665875923|page=44|date=April 15, 1920|title=Poverty Point|magazine=The Bulletin}}</ref>\n\n''The Lone Hand'' said it was the \"Best   Australian   production   to   date.   Station life   and   bush   scenes   well   depicted,   but   story  not   original.\"<ref>{{Cite web|magazine=The Lone Hand|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-393171752|title=Film Criticism|date=1 July 1920|page=34}}</ref>\n  \n''Australian Worker'' said the film was \"considerably better\" than ''Man from Kangaroo''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article146176930 |title=THE SHADOW OF LIGHTNING RIDGE. |newspaper=[[The Australian Worker]] |volume=29 |issue=11 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=11 March 1920 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nMeredyth and Lucas left for Sonoma on 11 February 1920 so were not in Australia when the film premiered.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title=The Lone hand\n  | date=1907\n  | publisher=W. McLeod]\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-393171651\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n===Box Office===\nThe film was a success at the Australian box office.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32066827 |title=AUSTRALIAN FILMS. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=23 November 1927 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=18 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{Citation\n  | title=Everyones\n  | date=1920\n  | publisher=Everyones Ltd\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-541859968\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref> Reportedly \"thousands\" witnessed it in its Melbourne season<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article34475005 |title=CAMPERDOWN CHRONICLE PUBLISHED EVERY TUESDAY, THURSDAY. SATURDAY SATURDAY, MAY 15, 1920. |newspaper=[[Camperdown Chronicle]] |volume=XLI |issue=4248 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=15 May 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and broke box office records in Newcastle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article138821985 |title=STRAND THEATRE. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |issue=14,216 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=1 June 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nDan Carroll later said his company \"was encouraged to consider making further pictures\" after the success of this and ''Man from Kangaroo''. He \"found, however, that small producers had entered the field, and, releasing pictures of a low duality, had made Australian films subjects for the ridicule of audiences. Lack of Australian stories suitable for dramatisation and the fact that oversea producers were releasing films more than sufficient for market needs had also forced him and his associates to abandon the production of films.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32066827 |title=AUSTRALIAN FILMS. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |volume=XLIII |issue=7,939 |location=Western Australia |date=23 November 1927 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe film was screened in Australian cinemas as late as 1923.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article143190670 |title=OXFORD THEATRE. |newspaper=[[The Daily Advertiser (Wagga Wagga)|Daily Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 May 1923 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n===US release===\nThe film was released in the US in 1922 by William Selig. One trade paper wrote that:\n<blockquote>\"Good stunt stuff is introduced in the film, and there are a few genuine thrills such as the leap from a dashing horse on to a speeding train; a kidnapping episode and a daring rescue. In connection with some of the stunts performed by Baker it would seem that either the director has been too hasty in an effort to get action or the film has not been carefully cut. At any rate, things happen along just a little too quickly to follow comprehensively. This is particularly noticeable in the instance where Baker rescues the girl he loves.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article243632442 |title=Footlights and Screen |newspaper=[[The Herald (Melbourne)|The Herald]] |issue=14,295 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=7 January 1922 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of lost films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0012668|title=The Shadow of Lightning Ridge}}\n*[http://colsearch.nfsa.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=no;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=the%20shadow%20of%20lightning%20ridge;querytype=;rec=6;resCount=10 ''The Shadow of Lightning Ridge]'' at [[National Film and Sound Archive]]\n*[http://silentera.com/PSFL/data/S/ShadowOfLightningRidge1920.html ''The Shadow of Lightning Ridge'' at SilentEra]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shadow of Lightning Ridge, The}}\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:1921 films]]\n[[Category:Australian drama films]]\n[[Category:Australian silent feature films]]\n[[Category:Australian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Bushranger films]]\n[[Category:Lost Australian films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bess Meredyth]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Wilfred Lucas]]\n[[Category:1920s drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Shadow of Lightning Ridge\n| image          = Shadow_of_Lightning_Ridge.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster \n| director       = [[Wilfred Lucas]]\n| producer       = [[E.J. Carroll]]<br>[[Snowy Baker]]\n| writer         = [[Bess Meredyth]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Snowy Baker]]<br>[[Agnes Vernon]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Robert Doerrer\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = Aywon Pictures (US)\n| studio          = Carroll-Baker Australian Productions\n| released       = 3 April 1920 (Australia)<br>13 September 1921 (US)\n| runtime        = 7 reels<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57918464 |title=\"SHADOW OF LIGHTNING RIDGE\" AT WEST'S. |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)|The Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=1 October 1920 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = [[Silent film]] <br>English intertitles\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n\n'''''The Shadow of Lightning Ridge''''' is a 1920 Australian [[silent film]] starring renowned Australian sportsman [[Snowy Baker]].<ref>{{Citation \n  | title=The Lone hand \n  | date=1907 \n  | publisher=W. McLeod \n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-393171672\n  | accessdate=4 June 2018\n}}</ref> It has been called the most \"Western\"-like of the films Baker made in Australia.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Filmink|first=Stephen|last=Vagg|title=50 Meat Pie Westerns|date=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt is now considered a [[lost film]].\n\n[[Charles Chauvel (filmmaker)|Charles Chauvel]] had a small role as a groom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article132858377 |title=TOPICS OF THE DAY |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald And Miners' Advocate]] |issue=21,972 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 March 1947 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110744601 |title=A RESOLUTE FILM MAKER |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=47 |issue=13,523 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=25 August 1973 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe success of the film prompted the formation of the Carroll-Baker Film Corporation with capital of \u00a325,000. A studio, Palmerston, at Waverly was established.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article222413479 |title=ALL AUSTRALIAN |newspaper=[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]] |issue=897 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 June 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nTravelling in a carriage is Sir Edward Marriott, a wealthy mine owner, his fianc\u00e9e Dorothy Hardyn, and a bag containing the month's pay for the miners. They are travelling to Marriott's estate at Lightning Ridge. There is also a man with a hacking cough.\n\nA conveyance with armed escort meets the train to prevent the large sum of money from a mysterious outlaw known as The Shadow. However The Shadow, the man with the hacking cough, gets the money and a necklace from the Dorothy. He jumps on to a horse and escapes.\n\nIt turns out the Shadow is actually a gentleman in disguise with a vendetta against Sir Edward because his mother has been victimised by him. He has become a The Shadow but only attacks Sir Edward's property.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article146689823 |title=THE SHADOW OF LIGHTNING RIDGE |newspaper=[[Table Talk (magazine)|Table Talk]] |issue=1810 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=1 April 1920 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe Shadow rescues Dorothy from real bushrangers and they fall in love. Later he discovers he is the real heir to Sir Edward's property. Portuguese Anne, who is in love with the Shadow, becomes jealous of Dorothy and arranges for the Shadow to be arrested. However he escapes.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57922010 \"WEST'S PICTURES.\" ''The Register (Adelaide)'' 28 Sep 1920: 6] accessed 18 December 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article138821985 |title=STRAND THEATRE. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald And Miners' Advocate]] |issue=14,216 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=1 June 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Snowy Baker]] as the Shadow\n*[[Agnes Vernon]] as Dorothy Harden\n*Bernice Vere as Portuguese Annie\n*[[Wilfred Lucas]] as Sir Edward Marriott\n*Evelyn Johnson<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120524924 |title=NEW AUSTRALIAN-MADE FILM |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Sydney)|The Sunday Times]] |issue=1790 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=16 May 1920 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Reg K Bisley as station guard<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-559440611|magazine=Everyone's|title=Along Film Row|date=22 April 1922|page=5}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe script was clearly inspired by [[Zorro]], which [[Bess Meredyth]] later adapted in ''[[The Mark of Zorro (1940 film)|The Mark of Zorro]]'' (1940). After reading the script and seeing the stunts he was required to perform, Baker reportedly went out and insured himself for \u00a35,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57922710 |title=AMUSEMENTS. |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)|The Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=30 September 1920 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nBernice Vere was a discovery of Baker's.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title=The bulletin\n  | date=1880\n  | publisher=John Haynes and J.F. Archibald\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-665875923\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref> She was signed to a 12-month contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article212993205 |title=[?] Baptist Association. |newspaper=[[Quorn Mercury]] |volume= |location=South Australia |date=10 September 1920 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nShooting took place in early 1920 in the bush near Sydney, at Bulli Pass and Loddon Falls<ref>{{Citation\n  | author1=Australian Geographical Society.\n  | author2=Australian National Publicity Association.\n  | author3=Australian National Travel Association.\n  | title=Walkabout\n  | date=1934\n  | publisher=Australian National Travel Association\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-751074193\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref> and at a studio built by [[E.J. Carroll]] at Palmerston near Waverly.<ref>[http://www.waverley.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/8739/PalmerstonStudio.pdf 'Palmerston Studio: Our pioneer silent film studio' Waverly Council]</ref>\n\nA highlight of the film was Snowy Baker on horseback jumping 40 metres off a cliff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57917030 |title=AUSTRALIAN-MADE FILMS. |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)|The Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=25 September 1920 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=10 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57922010 |title=WEST'S PICTURES. |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)|The Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=28 September 1920 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nBaker used a stuntman for some of the more dangerous scenes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article159028610 |title=NEWS OF THE FILM WORLD. |newspaper=[[Sydney Mail]] |volume=XVI |issue=415 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=10 March 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical===\nThe trade paper ''Everyone's'' said:\n<blockquote>Baker as an elusive bushranger brings joy to  the  hearts  of  the  Pussyfoots by entirely wrecking  a  bush pub.  Snowy  doesn\u2019t  do  it  on  behalf  of prohibition.  He\u2019s  escaping  from  the Law and the big  fight  that  ensues  causes the  damage.  It  was  thought  at  first that  the  big  scene  could  be  done  with empty  bottles  on  the  shelves,  but  so many  were  smashed  that  it  was  found that  there  was  a  sad  lack  of  realism. So,  to  the  horror  of  many  actors,  dozens of  bottles  of  real  whisky  were  deliberately  wasted.  Now,  it  is  said,  \"  The Shadow  of  Lightning  Ridge\"  is  certain of  a  tremendous  success  especially  after 6  p.m.  Thirsty  folk  will  go  along  just to  smell  the  bush  pubs  scene.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title=Everyones\n  | date=1920\n  | publisher=Everyones Ltd\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-536053965\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe ''Bulletin'' praised the photography but thought the story was too American saying the \"only Australian   thing   about\" the movie \"is   the   setting.  The   scenery   is   dinkum,   but   the   story   itself   is  a   mixture   of   old   melodrama   and   Wild   West  movie.   Australia   wants   Australian   films,   and  \nin   spite   of   \"Snowy\"   Baker's   great   athletic  business,   she   will   refuse   to   swallow   \"The  Shadow\"   as   the   thing   her   soul   cries   for.  \nLeading-woman   Brownie   Vernon,   also   being  American,   adds   nothing   Australian   to   the  picture.   But   the   photography   is   excellent.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine|magazine=The Bulletin|page=36|title=Sundry Shows|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-626908532|date=May 20, 1920}}</ref> Another article in the same magazine said the film \"claims   Australian   patronage   on   account   of  its   local   production,   but   is   in   all   its   gun play   and   other   effects   imitation   American.  Heaven   forbid   that   this   sort   of   stuff   should  go   out   to   the   world   as   dinkum   Australian   !\" <ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-665875923|page=44|date=April 15, 1920|title=Poverty Point|magazine=The Bulletin}}</ref>\n\n''The Lone Hand'' said it was the \"Best   Australian   production   to   date.   Station life   and   bush   scenes   well   depicted,   but   story  not   original.\"<ref>{{Cite web|magazine=The Lone Hand|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-393171752|title=Film Criticism|date=1 July 1920|page=34}}</ref>\n  \n''Australian Worker'' said the film was \"considerably better\" than ''Man from Kangaroo''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article146176930 |title=THE SHADOW OF LIGHTNING RIDGE. |newspaper=[[The Australian Worker]] |volume=29 |issue=11 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=11 March 1920 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nMeredyth and Lucas left for Sonoma on 11 February 1920 so were not in Australia when the film premiered.<ref>{{Citation\n  | title=The Lone hand\n  | date=1907\n  | publisher=W. McLeod]\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-393171651\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n===Box Office===\nThe film was a success at the Australian box office.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32066827 |title=AUSTRALIAN FILMS. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=23 November 1927 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |page=18 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{Citation\n  | title=Everyones\n  | date=1920\n  | publisher=Everyones Ltd\n  | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-541859968\n  | accessdate=14 March 2019\n}}</ref> Reportedly \"thousands\" witnessed it in its Melbourne season<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article34475005 |title=CAMPERDOWN CHRONICLE PUBLISHED EVERY TUESDAY, THURSDAY. SATURDAY SATURDAY, MAY 15, 1920. |newspaper=[[Camperdown Chronicle]] |volume=XLI |issue=4248 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=15 May 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and broke box office records in Newcastle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article138821985 |title=STRAND THEATRE. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald And Miners' Advocate]] |issue=14,216 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=1 June 1920 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nDan Carroll later said his company \"was encouraged to consider making further pictures\" after the success of this and ''Man from Kangaroo''. He \"found, however, that small producers had entered the field, and, releasing pictures of a low duality, had made Australian films subjects for the ridicule of audiences. Lack of Australian stories suitable for dramatisation and the fact that oversea producers were releasing films more than sufficient for market needs had also forced him and his associates to abandon the production of films.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32066827 |title=AUSTRALIAN FILMS. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |volume=XLIII |issue=7,939 |location=Western Australia |date=23 November 1927 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=18 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe film was screened in Australian cinemas as late as 1923.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article143190670 |title=OXFORD THEATRE. |newspaper=[[The Daily Advertiser (Wagga Wagga)|Daily Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 May 1923 |accessdate=28 July 2019 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n===US release===\nThe film was released in the US in 1922 by William Selig. One trade paper wrote that:\n<blockquote>\"Good stunt stuff is introduced in the film, and there are a few genuine thrills such as the leap from a dashing horse on to a speeding train; a kidnapping episode and a daring rescue. In connection with some of the stunts performed by Baker it would seem that either the director has been too hasty in an effort to get action or the film has not been carefully cut. At any rate, things happen along just a little too quickly to follow comprehensively. This is particularly noticeable in the instance where Baker rescues the girl he loves.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article243632442 |title=Footlights and Screen |newspaper=[[The Herald (Melbourne)|The Herald]] |issue=14,295 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=7 January 1922 |accessdate=14 March 2019 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of lost films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0012668|title=The Shadow of Lightning Ridge}}\n*[http://colsearch.nfsa.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=no;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=the%20shadow%20of%20lightning%20ridge;querytype=;rec=6;resCount=10 ''The Shadow of Lightning Ridge]'' at [[National Film and Sound Archive]]\n*[http://silentera.com/PSFL/data/S/ShadowOfLightningRidge1920.html ''The Shadow of Lightning Ridge'' at SilentEra]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shadow of Lightning Ridge, The}}\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:1921 films]]\n[[Category:Australian drama films]]\n[[Category:Australian silent feature films]]\n[[Category:Australian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Bushranger films]]\n[[Category:Lost Australian films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bess Meredyth]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Wilfred Lucas]]\n[[Category:1920s drama films]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Shadow_of_Lightning_Ridge"}
{"title_page": "Barunga, Northern Territory", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{for2|the mountain range in South Australia|[[Barunga Range]]|the South Australia locality|[[Barunga Gap, South Australia|Barunga Gap]]}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type      = town\n| name      = Barunga\n| state     = nt\n| coordinates = {{coord|14|31|15|S|132|51|54|E|display=inline,title}}\n| image     = \n| caption   = \n| lga       = [[Roper Gulf Region]]\n| pop       = 313\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2011}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=\"Census2011\">{{Census 2011 AUS| id=SSC70019 |name=Barunga (State Suburb)| accessdate=15 September 2016|quick=on}}</ref>\n| postcode  = 0852\n| est       = \n| fedgov    = [[Division of Lingiari|Lingiari]]\n}}\n'''Barunga''', formerly known as '''Beswick Creek''' and then '''Bamyili''', is a small [[Aboriginal Australian|Aboriginal]] community located approximately {{convert|80|km}} southeast of [[Katherine, Northern Territory|Katherine]], in the [[Northern Territory]] of Australia. It is part of the [[Roper Gulf Region]] local government area. At the {{CensusAU|2011}}, Barunga had a population of 313.<ref name=Census2011/> \n\nIn mid June each year, the '''Barunga Festival''', a three-day event showcasing [[Australian Aboriginal culture]], is held. At the 1988 event, the '''Barunga Statement''', which requested a treaty between the [[Australian federal government]] and [[Indigenous Australians]] ([[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal]] and [[Torres Strait Islander]] peoples), was presented to then Prime Minister [[Bob Hawke]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Tin Mine in the Northern Territory.jpg|thumb|Tin Mine at Maranboy]]\n\nAboriginal people have lived in Barunga and the surrounding region for thousands of years.\n===Maranboy tin mine===\nIn September 1913, a goldfield named [[Maranboy]] was declared for a period of two years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3273586 |title=PROCLAMATION. |newspaper=[[Northern Territory Times And Gazette]] |volume=XXXVIII |issue=2082 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=2 October 1913 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Maranboy was located {{convert|8|km}} from where Barunga is today.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barunga|url=http://ropergulf.nt.gov.au/our-communities/barunga/|website=Roper Gulf Regional Council|accessdate=12 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nTin was discovered at Maranboy in 1913 by prospectors Scharber and Richardson.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3291876 |title=Maranboy Tinfield. |newspaper=[[Northern Territory Times And Gazette]] |volume=XLI |issue=2343 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=5 October 1918 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Tin mines and a battery were operational in the same year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3289175 |title=Mining News |newspaper=[[Northern Territory Times And Gazette]] |volume=XLI |issue=2322 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=11 May 1918 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Prospectors of European, Chinese and Aboriginal descent worked at Maranboy. The mine closed in 1949 for repairs but never reopened.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49991551 |title=Living on Credit Maranboy Battery Still Closed Mines Dept. Inefficiency |newspaper=[[Northern Standard]] |volume=4 |issue=186 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=16 December 1949 |accessdate=12 August 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Many of the Aboriginal people who serviced the mine returned to Beswick Creek.\n[[File:Bamyili.jpg|thumb|Bamyili Town Council]]\n===Plane crash nearby===\nA [[Douglas DC-3]] belonging to the [[Dutch Air Force]] crash-landed near Beswick Creek or [[Wugularr|Beswick]] (now Wugularr) in 1947.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49980609 |title=Dutch Dakota Crashed East of Katherine Gorge: Search Party on Way |newspaper=[[Northern Standard]] |volume=2 |issue=14 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=3 April 1947 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> All passengers survived, with four crew travelling about {{convert|100|mi}} down the Katherine River to get help. After running out of food they killed one of two dogs they had with them.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49980571 |title=Crew Of Crashed Dakota Eat |newspaper=[[Northern Standard]] |volume=2 |issue=14 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=3 April 1947 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The wings were eventually removed and the remains of the plane were towed to Katherine.<ref>{{cite document|title=Aeroplane|publisher=Northern Territory Library|hdl=10070/6369|date=January 1949|last1=Evans|first1=Ted}}</ref>\n\n===Tandangal===\n\nThe '''Tandangal''' Native Settlement (from [[Jawoyn language]] ''dangdangdal''), also known as the Eight Mile Settlement, was established in 1947, located about {{convert|13|km}} from Beswick Station. The local people were not consulted about the choice of location nor the method of their removal to the settlement from the King River Compound.<ref name=smith>{{cite book| title=Country, Kin and Culture | website=Google Books | url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Country_Kin_and_Culture.html?id=VSwlddVCxWYC|first=Claire|last=Smith|date=2004|isbn=9781862545755|publisher= Wakefield Press |p=39\u201343| access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, the Beswick community moved to Tandangal (sometimes known as \"old Bamyili\"<ref>{{cite web | last=Kuipers | first=Ludo | title=Tandangal - Beswick region - Northern Territory - Australia | website=OzOutback | date=18 February 1982 | url=https://ozoutback.com.au/Australia/beswick/slides/1982021802.html | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>), because of risk of flooding from recent heavy rains. An influenza epidemic spread through the community in May 1951.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48633362 |title=Fever Among Natives |newspaper=[[Barrier Miner]] |volume=LXIII |issue=17,396 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=26 February 1951 |accessdate=12 August 2016 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1951 the people were relocated to the new site, initially known as Beswick Creek Native Settlement, and Tandangal was condemned.<ref name=smith/>\n\n===Back to Beswick===\nBy November 1951 the 'flu had killed seven people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140332754 |title=Mystery 'Flu Kills 7 Aborigines |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |issue=23,428 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 November 1951 |accessdate=12 August 2016 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1951, the [[Northern Territory Government]] started to develop the Beswick Creek community, building basic housing infrastructure and creating some minor employment opportunities. Local farmers also employed Aboriginal people, even running a peanut farm at Beswick Creek. The farm only lasted a few years. As Beswick grew, new groups formed a camp on the other side of the river known as \"The Compound\" where the people made [[humpy|humpies]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n===1950s to present===\nThe Barunga school was first opened in 1954 with 42 children enrolled.{{cn|date=January 2020}} \n\nThe elders changed the name of \"The Compound\" to Bamyili in 1965. In 1984, it changed its name to Barunga.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nAustralian cycling champion [[Cadel Evans]] spent his early childhood in Barunga, in the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edmund|first1=Sam|title=Cadel Evans interview: I do about a quarter of the riding I used to ... about 10,000km a year now|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/cadel-evans-interview-i-do-about-a-quarter-of-the-riding-i-used-to--about-10000km-a-year-now/news-story/585271656f8335f480316ca69f5d1b20|accessdate=10 August 2016|agency=Herald Sun|date=9 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 the Barunga Festival was first held. In 1988, the Barunga Statement was presented to the [[Prime Minister]] at the event. (See below for detail.)\n\n==Barunga Festival==\n[[Bangardi Robert Lee]] (1852\u20132005), a leader of the [[Jawoyn|Bagala]] clan of the [[Jawoyn]] people, initiated the Barunga Sport and Cultural Festival in 1985. It became an important forum for sharing ideas, showcasing the [[Aboriginal Australian]] and [[Torres Strait Islander]] cultures and talent, and to engage with social and political issues.<ref name=aiatsisbarunga>{{cite web | title=The Barunga Statement | website=Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies | date=29 May 2018 | url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/barunga-statement | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nIt has become an annual music and cultural celebration, held on the [[Queen's Official Birthday#Australia|Queen's Birthday]] long weekend (second weekend) in June. It features a program of workshops, dancing [[Aboriginal ceremony|ceremonies]], traditional [[bush tucker]]-gathering, [[didgeridoo]]-making, [[Basket weaving#Australia|basket weaving]] and musical performances and sport.<ref>{{cite web|title=About the festival and how to get there|url=http://barungafestival.com.au/index.php/about/|website=Barunga Festival|accessdate=10 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815193149/http://barungafestival.com.au/index.php/about/|archive-date=15 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Barunga Festival 2018\">{{cite web | title=About | website=Barunga Festival | date=10 June 2018 | url=https://www.barungafestival.com.au/about | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Indigenous.gov.au 2018\">{{cite web | title=Barunga Festival impresses again | website=Indigenous.gov.au | date=22 June 2018 | url=https://www.indigenous.gov.au/news-and-media/stories/barunga-festival-impresses-again | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=={{anchor|statement}}The Barunga Statement==\nIn 1988, as part of [[Australian Bicentenary#1988|Bicentennial]] celebrations, the [[Prime Minister of Australia]] Bob Hawke visited the Northern Territory for the Barunga Festival, where he was presented with a statement of Aboriginal political objectives by [[Galarrwuy Yunupingu]] and [[Wenten Rubuntja]].<ref name=\"Barunga\">{{cite web|url=http://www1.aiatsis.gov.au/exhibitions/treaty/barunga.htm |title=Barunga Statement |last=Howie-Willis |first=Ian |year=2001 |publisher=The Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies (AIATSIS) |accessdate=2008-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717022315/http://www1.aiatsis.gov.au/exhibitions/treaty/barunga.htm |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref> Painted on a 1.2 metre square sheet of composite wood, it became known as the \"Barunga Statement\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article122398927 |title=Message 'very fitting' last act for Hawke |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=66 |issue=20,706 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=21 December 1991 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> It stated:\n\n{{poemquote\n|text=We, the Indigenous owners and occupiers of Australia, call on the Australian Government and people to recognise our rights:\n:to self-determination and self-management, including the freedom to pursue our own economic, social, religious and cultural development;\n:to permanent control and enjoyment of our ancestral lands;\n:to compensation for the loss of use of our lands, there having been no extinction of original title;\n:to protection of and control of access to our sacred sites, sacred objects, artefacts, designs, knowledge and works of art;\n:to the return of the remains of our ancestors for burial in accordance with our traditions;\n:to respect for and promotion of our [[Australian Aboriginal identity|Aboriginal identity]], including the cultural, linguistic, religious and historical aspects, and including the right to be educated in our own languages and in our own culture and history;\n:in accordance with the universal declaration of human rights, the international covenant on economic, social and cultural rights, the international covenant on civil and political rights, and the international convention on :the elimination of all forms of racial discrimination, rights to life, liberty, security of person, food, clothing, housing, medical care, education and employment opportunities, necessary social services and other basic rights.\nWe call on the Commonwealth to pass laws providing:\n:A national elected Aboriginal and Islander organisation to oversee Aboriginal and Islander affairs;\n:A national system of land rights;\n:A police and justice system which recognises our customary laws and frees us from discrimination and any activity which may threaten our identity or security, interfere with our freedom of expression or association, or otherwise prevent our full enjoyment and exercise of universally recognised human rights and fundamental freedoms.\nWe call on the Australian Government to support Aborigines in the development of an international declaration of principles for indigenous rights, leading to an international covenant.\nAnd we call on the Commonwealth Parliament to negotiate with us a Treaty recognising our prior ownership, continued occupation and sovereignty and affirming our human rights and freedom.<ref name=statement>{{cite web|title=Barunga Statement presented to Prime Minister Bob Hawke in 1988|url=http://www.australia.gov.au/about-australia/australian-story/bark-petition-barunga-1988|website=australia.gov.au|publisher=Australian Government|accessdate=10 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731230435/http://www.australia.gov.au/about-australia/australian-story/bark-petition-barunga-1988|archive-date=31 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\nPrime Minister Hawke responded by saying that he wished to conclude a treaty between Aboriginal and other Australians by 1990, but his wish was not fulfilled. Controversy erupted over the exposure of sacred material in the [[bark painting]], leading some Indigenous leaders to call for its return. Some leaders alleged the presentation of the painting resulted in at least ten deaths due to \"munya\", which translates as remorse in the Aboriginal system of payback.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120857700 |title=Aboriginal plea on 'payback' painting |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=64 |issue=19,751 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=5 November 1989 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Hawke's last act as Prime Minister was to hang the Barunga Statement at [[Parliament House, Canberra]]. He did so one minute before [[Paul Keating]] was sworn in as the new Prime Minister, stating \"its presence here calls on those who follow me, it demands of them that they continue efforts that they find solutions to the abundant problems that still face the Aboriginal people of this country\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article122398927 |title=Message 'very fitting' last act for Hawke |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=66 |issue=20,706 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=21 December 1991 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n===Yothu Yindi song ''Treaty''===\nIn June 1991 Australian Aboriginal band, [[Yothu Yindi]], wrote and released the hit song \"[[Treaty (song)|Treaty]]\" to commemorate the statement. Lead singer [[Mandawuy Yunupingu]], with his older brother [[Galarrwuy Yunupingu|Galarrwuy]], wanted to highlight the lack of progress on the treaty between Aboriginal peoples and the Federal Government. Mandawuy said:\n\n<blockquote>\"Bob Hawke visited the Territory. He went to this gathering in Barunga. And this is where he made a statement that there shall be a treaty between black and white Australia. Sitting around the camp fire, trying to work out a chord to the guitar, and around that camp fire, I said, \"Well, I heard it on the radio. And I saw it on the television.\" That should be a catchphrase. And that's where 'Treaty' was born\".<ref name=\"GNT\">{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/gnt/profiles/Transcripts/s1150380.htm |title=''George Negus Tonight'' Profiles - Transcripts - Mandawuy Yunupingu |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) |date=2004-07-08 |accessdate=2008-11-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606014348/http://www.abc.net.au/gnt/profiles/Transcripts/s1150380.htm |archive-date=2008-06-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref></blockquote> The song became a worldwide success.\n\n==Facilities==\nBarunga School provides education for students students from preschool to the middle years, with up to [[Year 12]] supported by the NT Open Education Centre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barunga|url=https://www.teachintheterritory.nt.gov.au/schools/barunga-school|website=Teach in the Territory|publisher=Northern Territory Government|accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020}}, the school is developing links with [[Wugularr]] and [[Bulman, Northern Territory|Bulman]] schools through the [[Vocational Education and Training]] (VET) program. The school has six 6 teaching staff and 14 non-teaching staff, with 54 boys and 48 girl students, 99% with languages other than English as a first language. As a very remote school in an area of [[socioeconomic]] disadvantage, at this point most of its students do not fall into the top quarter of achievement (as per the [[NAPLAN]] statistics,<ref name=school2018>{{cite web | title=School profile: Barunga School, Barunga, NT (2018) | website=My School | url=https://myschool.edu.au/school/50079/profile/2018| access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> but the number has been growing since 2011.<ref name=school2011>{{cite web | title=School profile: Barunga School, Barunga, NT (2011) | website=My School | url=https://myschool.edu.au/school/50079/profile/2011| access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Bagala Community Store opened in September 2017, after local women raised the need for good food at affordable prices. Run by eight staff, it is the only store in the NT entirely owned and operated by Indigenous people. it stocks fresh produce and other foods, as well as [[Household hardware|hardware]], mechanical goods, small [[electrical appliance]]s as well as [[major appliances]].<ref name=nattimes>{{cite web | title=New store an all-Indigenous operation |website=National Indigenous Times|date=18 October 2017 | url=https://nit.com.au/new-store-indigenous-operation/ | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe community has a health clinic, camping grounds, sports oval, [[basketball]] courts, [[softball]] pitch and council office.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://barungafestival.com.au/ Barunga Festival Official Website]\n*{{cite web | title=The Barunga Statement | website=Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies | date=29 May 2018 | url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/barunga-statement}}\n\n\n{{Localities and communities of the Roper Gulf Region|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in the Northern Territory]]\n[[Category:Aboriginal communities in the Northern Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{for2|the mountain range in South Australia|[[Barunga Range]]|the South Australia locality|[[Barunga Gap, South Australia|Barunga Gap]]}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type      = town\n| name      = Barunga\n| state     = nt\n| coordinates = {{coord|14|31|15|S|132|51|54|E|display=inline,title}}\n| image     = \n| caption   = \n| lga       = [[Roper Gulf Region]]\n| pop       = 313\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2011}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=\"Census2011\">{{Census 2011 AUS| id=SSC70019 |name=Barunga (State Suburb)| accessdate=15 September 2016|quick=on}}</ref>\n| postcode  = 0852\n| est       = \n| fedgov    = [[Division of Lingiari|Lingiari]]\n}}\n'''Barunga''', formerly known as '''Beswick Creek''' and then '''Bamyili''', is a small [[Aboriginal Australian|Aboriginal]] community located approximately {{convert|80|km}} southeast of [[Katherine, Northern Territory|Katherine]], in the [[Northern Territory]] of Australia. It is part of the [[Roper Gulf Region]] local government area. At the {{CensusAU|2011}}, Barunga had a population of 313.<ref name=Census2011/> \n\nIn mid June each year, the '''Barunga Festival''', a three-day event showcasing [[Australian Aboriginal culture]], is held. At the 1988 event, the '''Barunga Statement''', which requested a treaty between the [[Australian federal government]] and [[Indigenous Australians]] ([[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal]] and [[Torres Strait Islander]] peoples), was presented to then Prime Minister [[Bob Hawke]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Tin Mine in the Northern Territory.jpg|thumb|Tin Mine at Maranboy]]\n\nAboriginal people have lived in Barunga and the surrounding region for thousands of years.\n===Maranboy tin mine===\nIn September 1913, a goldfield named [[Maranboy]] was declared for a period of two years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3273586 |title=PROCLAMATION. |newspaper=[[Northern Territory Times And Gazette]] |volume=XXXVIII |issue=2082 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=2 October 1913 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Maranboy was located {{convert|8|km}} from where Barunga is today.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barunga|url=http://ropergulf.nt.gov.au/our-communities/barunga/|website=Roper Gulf Regional Council|accessdate=12 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nTin was discovered at Maranboy in 1913 by prospectors Scharber and Richardson.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3291876 |title=Maranboy Tinfield. |newspaper=[[Northern Territory Times And Gazette]] |volume=XLI |issue=2343 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=5 October 1918 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Tin mines and a battery were operational in the same year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3289175 |title=Mining News |newspaper=[[Northern Territory Times And Gazette]] |volume=XLI |issue=2322 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=11 May 1918 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Prospectors of European, Chinese and Aboriginal descent worked at Maranboy. The mine closed in 1949 for repairs but never reopened.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49991551 |title=Living on Credit Maranboy Battery Still Closed Mines Dept. Inefficiency |newspaper=[[Northern Standard]] |volume=4 |issue=186 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=16 December 1949 |accessdate=12 August 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Many of the Aboriginal people who serviced the mine returned to Beswick Creek.\n[[File:Bamyili.jpg|thumb|Bamyili Town Council]]\n===Plane crash nearby===\nA [[Douglas DC-3]] belonging to the [[Dutch Air Force]] crash-landed near Beswick Creek or [[Wugularr|Beswick]] (now Wugularr) in 1947.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49980609 |title=Dutch Dakota Crashed East of Katherine Gorge: Search Party on Way |newspaper=[[Northern Standard]] |volume=2 |issue=14 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=3 April 1947 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> All passengers survived, with four crew travelling about {{convert|100|mi}} down the Katherine River to get help. After running out of food they killed one of two dogs they had with them.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49980571 |title=Crew Of Crashed Dakota Eat |newspaper=[[Northern Standard]] |volume=2 |issue=14 |location=Northern Territory, Australia |date=3 April 1947 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The wings were eventually removed and the remains of the plane were towed to Katherine.<ref>{{cite document|title=Aeroplane|publisher=Northern Territory Library|hdl=10070/6369|date=January 1949|last1=Evans|first1=Ted}}</ref>\n\n===Tandangal===\n\nThe '''Tandangal''' Native Settlement (from [[Jawoyn language]] ''dangdangdal''), also known as the Eight Mile Settlement, was established in 1947, located about {{convert|13|km}} from Beswick Station. The local people were not consulted about the choice of location nor the method of their removal to the settlement from the King River Compound.<ref name=smith>{{cite book| title=Country, Kin and Culture | website=Google Books | url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Country_Kin_and_Culture.html?id=VSwlddVCxWYC|first=Claire|last=Smith|date=2004|isbn=9781862545755|publisher= Wakefield Press |p=39\u201343| access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, the Beswick community moved to Tandangal (sometimes known as \"old Bamyili\"<ref>{{cite web | last=Kuipers | first=Ludo | title=Tandangal - Beswick region - Northern Territory - Australia | website=OzOutback | date=18 February 1982 | url=https://ozoutback.com.au/Australia/beswick/slides/1982021802.html | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>), because of risk of flooding from recent heavy rains. An influenza epidemic spread through the community in May 1951.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48633362 |title=Fever Among Natives |newspaper=[[Barrier Miner]] |volume=LXIII |issue=17,396 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=26 February 1951 |accessdate=12 August 2016 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1951 the people were relocated to the new site, initially known as Beswick Creek Native Settlement, and Tandangal was condemned.<ref name=smith/>\n\n===Back to Beswick===\nBy November 1951 the 'flu had killed seven people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140332754 |title=Mystery 'Flu Kills 7 Aborigines |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald And Miners' Advocate]] |issue=23,428 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 November 1951 |accessdate=12 August 2016 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1951, the [[Northern Territory Government]] started to develop the Beswick Creek community, building basic housing infrastructure and creating some minor employment opportunities. Local farmers also employed Aboriginal people, even running a peanut farm at Beswick Creek. The farm only lasted a few years. As Beswick grew, new groups formed a camp on the other side of the river known as \"The Compound\" where the people made [[humpy|humpies]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n===1950s to present===\nThe Barunga school was first opened in 1954 with 42 children enrolled.{{cn|date=January 2020}} \n\nThe elders changed the name of \"The Compound\" to Bamyili in 1965. In 1984, it changed its name to Barunga.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nAustralian cycling champion [[Cadel Evans]] spent his early childhood in Barunga, in the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edmund|first1=Sam|title=Cadel Evans interview: I do about a quarter of the riding I used to ... about 10,000km a year now|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/cadel-evans-interview-i-do-about-a-quarter-of-the-riding-i-used-to--about-10000km-a-year-now/news-story/585271656f8335f480316ca69f5d1b20|accessdate=10 August 2016|agency=Herald Sun|date=9 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 the Barunga Festival was first held. In 1988, the Barunga Statement was presented to the [[Prime Minister]] at the event. (See below for detail.)\n\n==Barunga Festival==\n[[Bangardi Robert Lee]] (1852\u20132005), a leader of the [[Jawoyn|Bagala]] clan of the [[Jawoyn]] people, initiated the Barunga Sport and Cultural Festival in 1985. It became an important forum for sharing ideas, showcasing the [[Aboriginal Australian]] and [[Torres Strait Islander]] cultures and talent, and to engage with social and political issues.<ref name=aiatsisbarunga>{{cite web | title=The Barunga Statement | website=Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies | date=29 May 2018 | url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/barunga-statement | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nIt has become an annual music and cultural celebration, held on the [[Queen's Official Birthday#Australia|Queen's Birthday]] long weekend (second weekend) in June. It features a program of workshops, dancing [[Aboriginal ceremony|ceremonies]], traditional [[bush tucker]]-gathering, [[didgeridoo]]-making, [[Basket weaving#Australia|basket weaving]] and musical performances and sport.<ref>{{cite web|title=About the festival and how to get there|url=http://barungafestival.com.au/index.php/about/|website=Barunga Festival|accessdate=10 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815193149/http://barungafestival.com.au/index.php/about/|archive-date=15 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Barunga Festival 2018\">{{cite web | title=About | website=Barunga Festival | date=10 June 2018 | url=https://www.barungafestival.com.au/about | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Indigenous.gov.au 2018\">{{cite web | title=Barunga Festival impresses again | website=Indigenous.gov.au | date=22 June 2018 | url=https://www.indigenous.gov.au/news-and-media/stories/barunga-festival-impresses-again | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=={{anchor|statement}}The Barunga Statement==\nIn 1988, as part of [[Australian Bicentenary#1988|Bicentennial]] celebrations, the [[Prime Minister of Australia]] Bob Hawke visited the Northern Territory for the Barunga Festival, where he was presented with a statement of Aboriginal political objectives by [[Galarrwuy Yunupingu]] and [[Wenten Rubuntja]].<ref name=\"Barunga\">{{cite web|url=http://www1.aiatsis.gov.au/exhibitions/treaty/barunga.htm |title=Barunga Statement |last=Howie-Willis |first=Ian |year=2001 |publisher=The Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies (AIATSIS) |accessdate=2008-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717022315/http://www1.aiatsis.gov.au/exhibitions/treaty/barunga.htm |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref> Painted on a 1.2 metre square sheet of composite wood, it became known as the \"Barunga Statement\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article122398927 |title=Message 'very fitting' last act for Hawke |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=66 |issue=20,706 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=21 December 1991 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> It stated:\n\n{{poemquote\n|text=We, the Indigenous owners and occupiers of Australia, call on the Australian Government and people to recognise our rights:\n:to self-determination and self-management, including the freedom to pursue our own economic, social, religious and cultural development;\n:to permanent control and enjoyment of our ancestral lands;\n:to compensation for the loss of use of our lands, there having been no extinction of original title;\n:to protection of and control of access to our sacred sites, sacred objects, artefacts, designs, knowledge and works of art;\n:to the return of the remains of our ancestors for burial in accordance with our traditions;\n:to respect for and promotion of our [[Australian Aboriginal identity|Aboriginal identity]], including the cultural, linguistic, religious and historical aspects, and including the right to be educated in our own languages and in our own culture and history;\n:in accordance with the universal declaration of human rights, the international covenant on economic, social and cultural rights, the international covenant on civil and political rights, and the international convention on :the elimination of all forms of racial discrimination, rights to life, liberty, security of person, food, clothing, housing, medical care, education and employment opportunities, necessary social services and other basic rights.\nWe call on the Commonwealth to pass laws providing:\n:A national elected Aboriginal and Islander organisation to oversee Aboriginal and Islander affairs;\n:A national system of land rights;\n:A police and justice system which recognises our customary laws and frees us from discrimination and any activity which may threaten our identity or security, interfere with our freedom of expression or association, or otherwise prevent our full enjoyment and exercise of universally recognised human rights and fundamental freedoms.\nWe call on the Australian Government to support Aborigines in the development of an international declaration of principles for indigenous rights, leading to an international covenant.\nAnd we call on the Commonwealth Parliament to negotiate with us a Treaty recognising our prior ownership, continued occupation and sovereignty and affirming our human rights and freedom.<ref name=statement>{{cite web|title=Barunga Statement presented to Prime Minister Bob Hawke in 1988|url=http://www.australia.gov.au/about-australia/australian-story/bark-petition-barunga-1988|website=australia.gov.au|publisher=Australian Government|accessdate=10 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731230435/http://www.australia.gov.au/about-australia/australian-story/bark-petition-barunga-1988|archive-date=31 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\nPrime Minister Hawke responded by saying that he wished to conclude a treaty between Aboriginal and other Australians by 1990, but his wish was not fulfilled. Controversy erupted over the exposure of sacred material in the [[bark painting]], leading some Indigenous leaders to call for its return. Some leaders alleged the presentation of the painting resulted in at least ten deaths due to \"munya\", which translates as remorse in the Aboriginal system of payback.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article120857700 |title=Aboriginal plea on 'payback' painting |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=64 |issue=19,751 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=5 November 1989 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Hawke's last act as Prime Minister was to hang the Barunga Statement at [[Parliament House, Canberra]]. He did so one minute before [[Paul Keating]] was sworn in as the new Prime Minister, stating \"its presence here calls on those who follow me, it demands of them that they continue efforts that they find solutions to the abundant problems that still face the Aboriginal people of this country\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article122398927 |title=Message 'very fitting' last act for Hawke |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=66 |issue=20,706 |location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia |date=21 December 1991 |accessdate=10 August 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n===Yothu Yindi song ''Treaty''===\nIn June 1991 Australian Aboriginal band, [[Yothu Yindi]], wrote and released the hit song \"[[Treaty (song)|Treaty]]\" to commemorate the statement. Lead singer [[Mandawuy Yunupingu]], with his older brother [[Galarrwuy Yunupingu|Galarrwuy]], wanted to highlight the lack of progress on the treaty between Aboriginal peoples and the Federal Government. Mandawuy said:\n\n<blockquote>\"Bob Hawke visited the Territory. He went to this gathering in Barunga. And this is where he made a statement that there shall be a treaty between black and white Australia. Sitting around the camp fire, trying to work out a chord to the guitar, and around that camp fire, I said, \"Well, I heard it on the radio. And I saw it on the television.\" That should be a catchphrase. And that's where 'Treaty' was born\".<ref name=\"GNT\">{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/gnt/profiles/Transcripts/s1150380.htm |title=''George Negus Tonight'' Profiles - Transcripts - Mandawuy Yunupingu |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) |date=2004-07-08 |accessdate=2008-11-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606014348/http://www.abc.net.au/gnt/profiles/Transcripts/s1150380.htm |archive-date=2008-06-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref></blockquote> The song became a worldwide success.\n\n==Facilities==\nBarunga School provides education for students students from preschool to the middle years, with up to [[Year 12]] supported by the NT Open Education Centre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barunga|url=https://www.teachintheterritory.nt.gov.au/schools/barunga-school|website=Teach in the Territory|publisher=Northern Territory Government|accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020}}, the school is developing links with [[Wugularr]] and [[Bulman, Northern Territory|Bulman]] schools through the [[Vocational Education and Training]] (VET) program. The school has six 6 teaching staff and 14 non-teaching staff, with 54 boys and 48 girl students, 99% with languages other than English as a first language. As a very remote school in an area of [[socioeconomic]] disadvantage, at this point most of its students do not fall into the top quarter of achievement (as per the [[NAPLAN]] statistics,<ref name=school2018>{{cite web | title=School profile: Barunga School, Barunga, NT (2018) | website=My School | url=https://myschool.edu.au/school/50079/profile/2018| access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> but the number has been growing since 2011.<ref name=school2011>{{cite web | title=School profile: Barunga School, Barunga, NT (2011) | website=My School | url=https://myschool.edu.au/school/50079/profile/2011| access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Bagala Community Store opened in September 2017, after local women raised the need for good food at affordable prices. Run by eight staff, it is the only store in the NT entirely owned and operated by Indigenous people. it stocks fresh produce and other foods, as well as [[Household hardware|hardware]], mechanical goods, small [[electrical appliance]]s as well as [[major appliances]].<ref name=nattimes>{{cite web | title=New store an all-Indigenous operation |website=National Indigenous Times|date=18 October 2017 | url=https://nit.com.au/new-store-indigenous-operation/ | access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe community has a health clinic, camping grounds, sports oval, [[basketball]] courts, [[softball]] pitch and council office.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://barungafestival.com.au/ Barunga Festival Official Website]\n*{{cite web | title=The Barunga Statement | website=Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies | date=29 May 2018 | url=https://aiatsis.gov.au/barunga-statement}}\n\n\n{{Localities and communities of the Roper Gulf Region|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in the Northern Territory]]\n[[Category:Aboriginal communities in the Northern Territory]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barunga,_Northern_Territory"}
{"title_page": "Austral (1881)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=StateLibQld 1 133561 Austral (ship).jpg\n|Ship caption=''Austral''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship name=''Austral''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=[[Orient Steam Navigation Company]], [[Glasgow]]\n|Ship builder=[[John Elder & Co.]], Govan\n|Ship yard number=245\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=21 December 1881\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship fate=Broken up at Genoa in 1903.\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption= \n|Ship class= 100 A1\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=5524 grt, 5588 after refit\n|Ship displacement= {{convert|9500|LT|MT}}\n|Ship length={{convert|470|ft}}<ref name=stats/>\n|Ship beam=\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught= \n|Ship depth= {{convert|37|ft}}\n|Ship power= {{convert|9000|hp}}\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 133557 Austral (ship).jpg|thumb|left|250px|''Austral'' settled on the bottom of Sydney Harbour in November 1882.]]\n'''''Austral''''' was a passenger ship built by [[John Elder & Co.]], Govan and launched on 21 December 1881 for the [[Orient Steam Navigation Company]], [[Glasgow]]. She was used in the passenger route trade to Australia.\n\nShe sank at her mooring in [[Neutral Bay, New South Wales|Neutral Bay]], off [[Kirribilli, New South Wales|Kirribilli]] Point in Sydney Harbour on 11 November 1882.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13523253 |title=SINKING OF THE S.S. AUSTRAL. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=13,923 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=13 November 1882|accessdate=11 May 2011|page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Five crew were killed in the [[Coastal coal-carrying trade of New South Wales#'Coal lumping' gangs|incident]].<ref name=\"Gillett\">{{Citation | author1=Gillett, Ross | author2=Melliar-Phelps, Michael, 1941- | title=A Century of Ships in Sydney Harbour | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/9600346?q&sort=holdings+desc&_=1478760115407&versionId=11140534 | date=1980 | publisher=Rigby | isbn=978-0-7270-1201-2 }}</ref> The ship was raised and sailed to Glasgow for refit.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137091375 |title=TELEGRAMS. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |volume=X |issue=3529 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=28 February 1883 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=stats>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28366686 |title=ARRIVAL OF THE R.M.S. AUSTRAL. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=14,594 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 January 1885 |page=7 |accessdate=11 May 2011 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nShe was chartered to [[Anchor Line (steamship company)|Anchor Line]] for 7 months during 1884<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13550847 |title=THE S.S. AUSTRAL. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=14,322 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 February 1884 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137284040 |title=Miscellaneous. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald and Miners' Advocate]] |volume=XI |issue=8393 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 February 1884 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> for the Liverpool to New York passenger route arriving back at Neutral Bay in 1885.\n\n==Fate==\n''Austral'' arrived for breaking up at Genoa on 27 May 1903.<ref name=\"Gillett\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons cat inline|Austral (ship, 1881)}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=506 | title=Clyde built ships - ''Austral''|url-status=usurped |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303225924/http://clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=506|archivedate=3 March 2016}}\n* {{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article64034239 |title=SINKING OF THE ORIENT S.S. \"AUSTRAL,\" IN SYDNEY HARBOUR. |newspaper=[[Illustrated Sydney News]] |volume=XIX |issue=12 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=25 November 1882 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n\n[[Category:1881 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Clyde]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1882]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=StateLibQld 1 133561 Austral (ship).jpg\n|Ship caption=''Austral''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship name=''Austral''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=[[Orient Steam Navigation Company]], [[Glasgow]]\n|Ship builder=[[John Elder & Co.]], Govan\n|Ship yard number=245\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=21 December 1881\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship fate=Broken up at Genoa in 1903.\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption= \n|Ship class= 100 A1\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=5524 grt, 5588 after refit\n|Ship displacement= {{convert|9500|LT|MT}}\n|Ship length={{convert|470|ft}}<ref name=stats/>\n|Ship beam=\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught= \n|Ship depth= {{convert|37|ft}}\n|Ship power= {{convert|9000|hp}}\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 133557 Austral (ship).jpg|thumb|left|250px|''Austral'' settled on the bottom of Sydney Harbour in November 1882.]]\n'''''Austral''''' was a passenger ship built by [[John Elder & Co.]], Govan and launched on 21 December 1881 for the [[Orient Steam Navigation Company]], [[Glasgow]]. She was used in the passenger route trade to Australia.\n\nShe sank at her mooring in [[Neutral Bay, New South Wales|Neutral Bay]], off [[Kirribilli, New South Wales|Kirribilli]] Point in Sydney Harbour on 11 November 1882.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13523253 |title=SINKING OF THE S.S. AUSTRAL. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=13,923 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=13 November 1882|accessdate=11 May 2011|page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Five crew were killed in the [[Coastal coal-carrying trade of New South Wales#'Coal lumping' gangs|incident]].<ref name=\"Gillett\">{{Citation | author1=Gillett, Ross | author2=Melliar-Phelps, Michael, 1941- | title=A Century of Ships in Sydney Harbour | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/9600346?q&sort=holdings+desc&_=1478760115407&versionId=11140534 | date=1980 | publisher=Rigby | isbn=978-0-7270-1201-2 }}</ref> The ship was raised and sailed to Glasgow for refit.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137091375 |title=TELEGRAMS. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald And Miners' Advocate]] |volume=X |issue=3529 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=28 February 1883 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=stats>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28366686 |title=ARRIVAL OF THE R.M.S. AUSTRAL. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=14,594 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 January 1885 |page=7 |accessdate=11 May 2011 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nShe was chartered to [[Anchor Line (steamship company)|Anchor Line]] for 7 months during 1884<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13550847 |title=THE S.S. AUSTRAL. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=14,322 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 February 1884 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137284040 |title=Miscellaneous. |newspaper=[[Newcastle Morning Herald And Miners' Advocate]] |volume=XI |issue=8393 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 February 1884 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> for the Liverpool to New York passenger route arriving back at Neutral Bay in 1885.\n\n==Fate==\n''Austral'' arrived for breaking up at Genoa on 27 May 1903.<ref name=\"Gillett\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons cat inline|Austral (ship, 1881)}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=506 | title=Clyde built ships - ''Austral''|url-status=usurped |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303225924/http://clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=506|archivedate=3 March 2016}}\n* {{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article64034239 |title=SINKING OF THE ORIENT S.S. \"AUSTRAL,\" IN SYDNEY HARBOUR. |newspaper=[[Illustrated Sydney News]] |volume=XIX |issue=12 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=25 November 1882 |accessdate=10 November 2016 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n\n[[Category:1881 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Clyde]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1882]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austral_(1881)"}
{"title_page": "Shaun the Sheep", "text_new": "{{short description|British stop-motion animated children's television series}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Shaun the Sheep\n| image                    = Shaun the Sheep logo.svg\n| genre                    = [[Comedy]]<br>[[Clay animation]]<br>[[Slice of life]]\n| creator                  = [[Nick Park]]\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''[[Wallace & Gromit]]''|[[Nick Park]]}}\n| developer                = [[Richard Starzak|Richard Goleszowski]]<br />[[Alison Snowden]]<br />[[David Fine (filmmaker)|David Fine]]\n| director                 = [[Richard Starzak|Richard Goleszowski]]<br />[[Christopher Sadler]]\n| voices                   = [[Justin Fletcher]]<br>[[John Sparkes]]<br />[[Kate Harbour]]<br />Richard Webber<br />[[Emma Tate (actress)|Emma Tate]] (2016)<br />[[Andy Nyman]] (2016)<br />[[Simon Greenall]] (2016)<br />[[Jo Allen (animation producer)|Jo Allen]] (2007)\n| theme_music_composer     = Mark Thomas\n| opentheme                = \"Life's a Treat\" by Mark Thomas and [[Vic Reeves]]\n| endtheme                 = \"Life's a Treat (Instrumental)\"\n| country                  = United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaun the Sheep (TV series) (2007)|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4f4baf319014e|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref>\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 6\n| num_episodes             = 170<br>36 (shorts)<br>1 (special)\n| list_episodes            = List of Shaun the Sheep episodes\n| executive_producer       = '''For Aardman Animations:''' <br />Miles Bullough<br />[[David Sproxton]]<br />[[Peter Lord]]<br />Nick Park<br />'''For BBC:'''<br />[[Michael Carrington (television executive)|Michael Carrington]]<br>Nikki Chaplin\n| producer                 = Julie Lockhart <small>(series 1)</small><br>Gareth Owen <small>(series 2)</small><br>John Woolley <small>(series 3 and 4)</small>\n| location                 = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 7 minutes\n| company                  = [[Aardman Animations]]<br>[[BBC]]<br>[[Westdeutscher Rundfunk]]\n| network                  = [[CBBC]] (Series 1-5)<br>[[BBC One]] (special)<br>[[Netflix]] (Series 6)\n| picture_format           = [[16:9]] widescreen [[PAL]] ([[576i]]) <small>(2007)</small><br />[[16:9]] [[HDTV]] ([[1080i]]) <small>(2009\u2013present)</small>\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital]] 5.1\n| first_run                = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|df=yes|2007|3|5|}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|df=yes|present}}\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = {{Plainlist |\n* ''[[Wallace and Gromit]]''\n* ''[[Timmy Time]]''\n| website              = http://www.shaunthesheep.com\n}}\n}}\n'''''Shaun the Sheep''''' is a British [[stop-motion]] [[animated]] television series [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of the ''[[Wallace and Gromit]]'' franchise.  The series stars Shaun &mdash; a [[sheep]] previously featured in the 1995 short film ''[[A Close Shave]]'' and in the ''Shopper 13'' short film from the 2002 ''[[Wallace and Gromit's Cracking Contraptions]]'' series &mdash; and his madcap adventures around a small farm as the leader of his flock.\n\nThe series was first aired in the UK on the [[CBBC]] block on [[BBC One]] on 5 March 2007. It has been broadcast in 180 countries globally. The series consists of 150 seven-minute episodes. The fifth series contains 20 episodes and was aired in the Netherlands from 1 December 2015 until 1 January 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yelotv.be/programma/shaun-het-schaap/seizoen_5/aflevering_1/de-redding-nabij- |title= Shaun the Sheep Season 5 |publisher=YeloTV|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vpro.nl/speel.POW_02521095.html |title=Shaun the Sheep: De redding nabij? (season 5, episode 1) |date=1 December 2016|publisher=VPRO|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vpro.nl/speel.POW_02521112.html |title=Shaun the Sheep: Timmy en de draak (season 5, episode 20) |date=1 January 2016|publisher=VPRO|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> and in Australia on ABC Kids from 16 January 2016 until 1 May 2016.\n\nThe series inspired its own spin-off, ''[[Timmy Time]]'', which follows the adventures of Shaun's small cousin and is aimed at younger viewers. A feature-length film, titled ''[[Shaun the Sheep Movie]]'', was released theatrically in 2015. A 30-minute film, titled ''[[Shaun the Sheep: The Farmer's Llamas]]'', was aired as a 2015 Christmas TV special. The second feature-length film, titled ''[[A Shaun the Sheep Movie: Farmageddon]]'', was released theatrically on 18 October 2019.\n\nThe series recently has migrated to [[Netflix]] for a sixth series, under the subtitle ''Adventures from Mossy Bottom''.\n\n== Plot ==\nShaun, an unusually bright and clever sheep, lives with his flock at Mossy Bottom Farm (the name being revealed in the fourth season), a traditional small northern English farm. In each episode, their latest attempt to add excitement to their dull mundane life as livestock somehow snowballs into a fantastic [[situational comedy|sitcom]]-style escapade, most often with the help of their fascination with human doings and devices. This usually brings them into conflict\u2014and often into partnership\u2014with the farm sheepdog Bitzer, while they all are simultaneously trying to avoid discovery by the Farmer.\n\n== Production ==\n\nThe show was produced by [[Aardman Animations]], and was commissioned by the [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC) and the [[Westdeutscher Rundfunk]] (WDR),<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeMott|first1=Rick|url=http://www.awn.com/news/aardman-s-shaun-sheep-munches-his-way-around-world |title=Aardman's Shaun The Sheep Munches His Way Around The World |date=19 October 2005|publisher=Animation World Network|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> a constituent member of the consortium of German public-broadcasting institutions, [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]]. It has aired on BBC channels in the UK from 2007 onwards.\n\nEach seven-minute episode is entirely shot in Aardman's distinctive [[stop-motion]] animation style. The comedic tone is a combination of [[slapstick]] and classic [[silent comedy]], similar to that used in the ''[[Wallace & Gromit]]'' shorts. In this series, there is not much spoken dialogue at all, even from the human characters; simple grunts, bleats, pointing, sighs, mutterings, words, and similar wordless inflections are all used to indicate each character's moods and motives. There are also no readable words in any episode, although \"Bitzer\" can be seen on a dog bowl, and\u2014in series four--\"Mossy Bottom Farm\" on a gate, in the original English-language title sequence. All other signage, such as on a pizza box or a bus stop, is replaced by an illegible scrawl and a picture.\n\nShaun the Sheep's first appearance was in Wallace & Gromit's third short feature, the [[Academy Award]] winning ''[[A Close Shave]]'', as the youngest member of a flock of sheep Wallace and Gromit work to save from being turned into dog food. He was named Shaun as a pun on the word \"shorn\" after he was accidentally subjected to Wallace's automated [[sheep shearing]] machine. This early version of Shaun shows a hint of his characteristic human-like bravado\u2014among other things, wearing a sweater knitted from his own shorn wool\u2014and he proves to be a major help in saving the day.\n\nAt the end of this short, Shaun is seen living with the duo; Shaun later made a brief cameo appearance in the \"Shopper 13\" episode of Wallace & Gromit's \"[[Cracking Contraptions]]\" web series. No official explanation has been given for the flock's transfer to the farm.\n\nAlthough the original series is silent aside from sound effects, a [[Hindi]]-dubbed version seen on [[Nickelodeon (India)|Nickelodeon India]] was redone with scripts and dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|author1=BestMediaInfo Bureau|title=Nickelodeon brings back \u2018Shaun the Sheep\u2019 in a new avatar|url=http://www.bestmediainfo.com/2012/08/nickelodeon-brings-back-%E2%80%98shaun-the-sheep%E2%80%99-in-a-new-avatar/|publisher=Best Media Info|accessdate=24 October 2015|date=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n{{main|List of Wallace and Gromit characters}}\n\n[[File:Richard Goleszowski.jpg|thumb|right|Series director Richard Goleszowski at Canterbury's Anifest 2008 with models of a generic sheep, Bitzer, Timmy, and Shaun]]\n\n=== Main ===\n*Shaun is the [[protagonist]] of the series and the leader of the flock. He is a clever, confident sheep, prone to mischief, but equally adept at getting himself and/or his friends out of it. As there is no dialogue, like all the sheep he communicates entirely through bleating, and often explains his ideas to the flock by drawing diagrams on a blackboard. He has a good friendship with Bitzer, though this does not stop him from playing pranks on him at times. \n*Bitzer <!-- discussion taken to Talk --Lexein -->is the farmer's loyal, long-suffering [[Herding dog|sheepdog]], dressed for work in a blue knit cap, black collar, knitted wristlet and large official-looking wrist-watch, carrying a clipboard and walking upright or on all fours as needed. He communicates, canine-fashion, via barks, growls, and the occasional whimper. He also gives instructions to the flock by blowing a whistle. Despite a tendency to be caught out listening to music, he takes his job very seriously, to the point of occasionally letting his power go to his head. He is however a generally good friend to Shaun and does his best to keep the whole flock out of trouble.\n*Shirley is the largest member of the flock. A gentle giant, she is usually seen placidly eating, though she's intimidating enough to have defended Shaun from Pidsley the cat. She's so big that large objects routinely disappear into her fleece, and she quite often gets stuck herself, needing the other sheep to push, pull or even sling-shot her out of trouble. However, her size can also come in very handy when what's needed is a battering ram or similarly immovable object. She is a devoted eater, blindly charging towards food, even if it isn't even food in the first place. Her size came from her eating, yet it has been proven that by following a diet and exercising, she can become as thin as Shaun.\n*Timmy, Shaun's cousin, is the flock's only lamb and thus often the innocent centre of the chaos. Timmy often tries to be like Shaun. His personality is often contrasting: sometimes he acts responsibly and understands what the older sheep say, other times, he acts as a normal baby, crying when something is taken from him or scares him. He\u2019s a toddler in series, and is often seen sucking a [[Pacifier|dummy]]. The spinoff series ''[[Timmy Time]]'' chronicles his later adventures in preschool.\n*Timmy's Mother, Shaun's Aunt, wears curlers in her topknot and is a bit careless about maternal duties, even using Timmy once as a makeshift paint brush. But when her offspring goes astray, she is inconsolable until he is safely back in her care.\n*Nuts is quite an eccentric, but useful sheep and usually, like the rest of the flock, accompanies and helps Shaun. But the thing that makes him stand out from the flock is that he has two different shaped eyes and a different shaped nose.\n*Hazel - Hazel's nerves often get the better of her. She's a timid little sheep who jumps at the slightest thing and can frequently be heard bleating nervously. When Farmer's caravan rolls off towards the city, Hazel can barely contain her fear \u2013 this is the stuff of nightmares! But when she finds herself carried along with the rest of the Flock in hot pursuit of a runaway caravan, Hazel discovers she's much braver than she ever imagined, and that while life in the city might be scary, it's good to face your fears every now and again.\n*The Flock, like typical sheep, tend to follow Shaun and one another, are obedient to orders and generally form one big happy if sometimes fractious family group. Unlike Shaun, however, they are not particularly bright, which becomes a problem when combined with their ongoing fascination with the human world. It's usually Shaun and Bitzer who sort out the resulting mess. \n*The Farmer is a bespectacled, balding man who runs the farm with Bitzer at his side and acts as the flock's primary if unwitting nemesis. His livestock's main concern is to ensure he remains completely oblivious to their unusual sentience, a task made easier by his conventional, unobservant nature but complicated by his enthusiasm for picking up new hobbies. He can be heard frequently making wordless noises or muttering under his breath ''just'' audibly enough for the viewer to pick up on his meaning. His disastrous attempts at dating are a running joke of the series. In the 2015 movie, he is referred to as Mr. X by those who don't know his identity.\n*The Naughty [[Pig|Pigs]], whose pen is adjacent to the sheepfield, are bullies to Shaun and his flock, always trying to antagonize them and get them into trouble. They are, however, scared of Bitzer (though they still take the chance to bully him whenever possible), and they get told off by the Farmer in \"Pig Trouble\".\n*Pidsley is the Farmer's orange [[cat]], a minor character (without fur) in Series 1 and the main antagonist of Series 2, who makes his last appearance in \"We Wish Ewe A Merry Christmas\".  He desires to be the sole recipient of the Farmer's attention and thus is jealous of Bitzer.  He also dislikes the sheep, thinking of them as stupid and beneath him.\n\n===Other===\n*Mower Mouth is a [[goat]] who first appears in the episode of the same name. He is an unstoppable eating machine. While not an unfriendly character, all of his considerable energy is focused on his next meal. He thus routinely causes trouble for Shaun and the flock, as also seen in \"Shaun the Farmer\".\n*The [[Bull]] is belligerent, powerful, and easily provoked by Shaun's antics and the colour red. He appears in \"The Bull\", \"Saturday Night Shaun\", \"Who's the Mummy?\" and \"Heavy Metal Shaun\".\n*The [[Duck|Ducks]] make frequent appearances. In the first series, a single duck gets into predicaments due to Shaun's exploits in \"Off the Baa!\", \"Tidy Up\", and \"Bathtime\". Sometimes he is seen with his lady friends. In series two there are two ducks; in series three, they have once again been replaced with a single, pure white duck.\n*The [[Extraterrestrials in fiction|Aliens]] appear in \"Shaun Encounters\", \"The Visitor\" and \"Cat Got Your Brain\" and briefly in \"Spring Lamb\".  They are green and have one large eye on the top of the head. Despite their clearly advanced scientific technology, which frequently causes trouble for the farm animals, they exhibit human-like behaviour and generally jovial personalities.\n*The Granny is a short-tempered, short-sighted old lady, appearing in \"Take Away\" and \"Save the Tree\". She also appears in \"Two's Company\", holding a cart, and \"The Big Chase\", forcing the pigs to give her a lift in their car. She is renowned for hitting people (or animals) with her handbag when they annoy her by mistake.\n*The Pizza Delivery Boy is a young man who rides a [[moped]] (which Bitzer often \"borrows\" to chase after the sheep) and works in the local [[pizzeria]]. He also works as a postman in \"Saturday Night Shaun\".\n*The Farmer's Girlfriend appears for the first time in Series 2. She appears to be adventurous and an animal lover, patting Bitzer and Shaun and offering food to Timmy.\n*The Farmer's Niece appears in \"The Farmer's Niece\", \"Bitzer's New Hat\" and \"The Rabbit\". She appears to be a fan of [[Horse|horses]] and causes irritation to Shaun, Bitzer and the flock. The Farmer's Niece is also a spoiled brat, as she screams and wails every time things don't go her way. She is also one of the few humans who know what the flock are up to.\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Main|List of Shaun the Sheep episodes}}\n\nThe first two series consisted of 40 seven-minute episodes each, and the third 20 episodes. The fourth series debuted on 3 February 2014.<ref name=BBC20140203>{{cite web|title=CBBC - Schedules, Monday 3 February 2014|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cbbc/programmes/schedules/2014/02/03|publisher=BBC|date=3 February 2014|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref> The fifth series aired in ABC Australia in January 2016. A series of 15 1-minute [[stereoscopic 3D|3D]] shorts were released on [[Nintendo]]'s [[Nintendo Video|Video service]] for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] between March and June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.game.co.uk/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/ArticleView?articleId=165521&catalogId=10201&langId=44&storeId=10151 |title=Shaun the Sheep 3D shorts coming to Nintendo Video |publisher=GAME |date=20 February 2012 |accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> The Nintendo shorts was released in early 2016 on the official ''Shaun the Sheep'' YouTube channel under the name \"Mossy Bottom Farm Shorts\".<ref>{{cite web|author1=Shaun the Sheep|title=Mossy Bottom Farm Shorts - Shaun the Sheep (Coming soon!)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Vg09KFg_dM|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=11 January 2016|date=8 January 2016}}</ref> Another series of 21 1-minute sports-themed shorts, named ''Championsheeps'', aired on CBBC during the Summer of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaun The Sheep Championsheeps|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/childrens2012/cbbc/shaun-the-sheep.html|accessdate=24 October 2015|publisher=BBC|date=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{:List of Shaun the Sheep episodes}}\n\n===Television specials===\nA half-hour television special based on the television series, titled ''[[Shaun the Sheep: The Farmer's Llamas]]'', premiered on [[BBC One]] on [[Boxing Day]] 2015.<ref name=AMFirstSpecial>{{cite news|last1=Milligan|first1=Mercedes|title=Shaun the Sheep Gets First Half-Hour Special|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/shaun-the-sheep-gets-first-half-hour-special/|accessdate=24 October 2014|work=Animation Magazine|date=15 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nA second half hour special will go into production in late 2020 and will air at Christmas 2021 on the BBC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/shaun-the-sheep|title=BBC - A Winter\u2019s Tale From Shaun The Sheep coming to BBC One - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/shaun-sheep-flocks-bbc-2021-105458924.html|title=\u2018Shaun The Sheep\u2019 Flocks To The BBC & Netflix For A 2021 Christmas Special|website=uk.movies.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Shaun the Sheep: Adventures from Mossy Bottom ===\nOn 19 February 2020 it was reported that a new Shaun the Sheep series called 'Shaun the Sheep: Adventures from Mossy Bottom' would be released on Netflix on 16 March 2020 in Spain, Poland, Turkey, Israel, and UAE. Additionally, it was released in the UK, US, Canada, and Latin America on 17 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/new-shaun-the-sheep-series-joins-netflix-flock-in-march/|title=New \u2018Shaun the Sheep\u2019 Series Joins Netflix Flock in March|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|date=19 February 2020|website=Animation Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nReviews of the series were consistently positive. Harry Venning of \"The Stage\" found \"characterisation charming and the animation superb. All this before even a mention of how funny and splendidly slapstick the script is.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Venning|first1=Harry|title=TV Review|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/16183/tv-review|accessdate=24 October 2015|work=The Stage|date=12 March 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930163623/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/16183/tv-review|archivedate=30 September 2007}}</ref>\nThe Guardian noted that the series \"hits the four-to-seven-year-old age group smack in the eye.\"<ref>Banks-Smith, Nancy (6 March 2007). [https://www.theguardian.com/tv_and_radio/story/0,,2027294,00.html Last Night's TV]. [[The Guardian]] (UK). Retrieved 3 April 2007.</ref>\nGareth Owen, the producer of the series, said Shaun the Sheep is aimed at viewers \"aged four to seven, though in reality, the age range is four to 87\", as the series became popular among all different age-groups.<ref>{{cite news|title=The painstaking production of Shaun the Sheep|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/6617069/The-painstaking-production-of-Shaun-the-Sheep.html|accessdate=24 October 2015|work=The Telegraph|date=20 November 2009}}</ref> Charles Arthur wrote \"classic Aardman style that leaves me laughing out loud.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arthur|first1=Charles|title=Roll over, Pixar \u2013 Shaun the sheep's here to tickle your funny bone|url=http://www.charlesarthur.com/blog/2007/03/20/roll-over-pixar-shaun-the-sheeps-here-to-tickle-your-funny-bone/|publisher=Charles Arthur|accessdate=24 October 2015|date=20 March 2007}}</ref>\n<!-- Charles Arthur's BLOG review is included here because he is an established print journalist. This was one of three reviews found as of 3 April 2007. It can/should go away when more reviews appear in legit press. --Lexein -->\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:95%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Awards\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipients and nominees\n! Result\n|-\n|[[British Academy Children's Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Children's in 2010|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2010/childrens|publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>\n| Animation in 2010\n| Gareth Owen, Richard Webber, Chris Sadler\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[British Academy Children's Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Children's in 2014|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2014/childrens|publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>\n| Animation in 2014\n| Richard Starzak, Jay Grace, John Woolley\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[British Academy Children's Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Children's in 2015|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2015/childrens|publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>\n| Animation in 2015\n| John Woolley, [[Steve Box]], Lee Wilton\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[International Emmy Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Foster|first1=Elizabeth|title=International Emmy Kids Awards announces nominees|url=http://kidscreen.com/2016/10/17/international-emmy-kids-awards-announce-nominees/|publisher=Kidscreen|accessdate=17 October 2016|date=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n| [[List of International Emmy Award winners#Kids: Animation|Kids:Animation]]\n| \n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|[[British Academy Children's Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Children's in 2016|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2016/childrens|publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts|accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref>\n| Animation in 2016\n| \n|{{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n== References to popular culture ==\n<!-- {{In popular culture|date=May 2011}} - irrelevant, those are refs TO popcult, not IN -->\n\n<!-- if notable (noted in published reviews), should be in main text --Lexein-->\nAs with the series' parent show Wallace and Gromit, there are many allusions to other aspects of [[popular culture]] and movies such as ''[[Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope|Star Wars]]'', ''[[The Lion King]]'', ''[[E.T.: The Extra-Terrestrial]]'', ''[[The Matrix]]'', and ''[[Pulp Fiction]]''. These include:\n* Shirley's training in the episode \"Shape Up with Shaun\" is based on the film ''[[Rocky]]''.\n* The paintings parodied in \"Still Life\" include the ''[[Mona Lisa]] ''and Constable's ''[[The Hay Wain]]''.\n* In \"Buzz Off Bees\", the Farmer appears in his hooded beekeepers outfit, with accompanying [[Darth Vader]]-style heavy breathing.\n* The infamous shower scene from ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' is spoofed in the episode \"The Little Sheep of Horrors\", whose name is itself  based on the film and play  ''[[The Little Shop of Horrors]]''.\n* In \"Hiccups\", Shaun turns his guitar amplifier up to 11 in a reference to a scene in ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]''.\n*In \"Fleeced\", at the beginning of episode when the farmer switches on the shearing machine in front of the frightened flock, it is a reference to Tobe Hooper's ''[[The Texas Chain Saw Massacre]]'', especially when the farmer grabs the sheep and drags it into the shearing room and jerkily closes the metal door after him - this is a reference to the scene from same film where the crazy masked killer with the chainsaw catches his victim in his killing room and closes its doors after him.<ref>The Texas Chainsaw Massacre</ref> The sheep break out and the accompanying music is very reminiscent of British [[World War II]] [[prisoner of war]] films (e.g., ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'')\n* In \"The Visitor\", the alien thrashes his car with a tree branch \u00e0 la [[Basil Fawlty]].\n* In \"Mountains out of Molehills\" a sheep is reading a magazine called \"Bleat\", a spoof of celebrity gossip magazine \"[[Heat (magazine)|Heat]]\". In the same episode, Shaun tries to catch a mole with a fishing rod and line. When the first \"bite\" is shown, the first two notes of the ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'' theme are played.\n* Near the end of \"Off the Baa\", the  \"[[Nessun Dorma]]\" theme from [[Puccini]]'s opera ''[[Turandot]]'' is used, which was the musical theme of the BBC's coverage of the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]]. The episode itself featured Shaun and the rest of the flock engaging in a football game with Bitzer as the referee.\n* At the end of \"Mower Mouth\" the shrubs are clearly reminiscent of those in ''[[Edward Scissorhands]]''.\n* In \"Saturday Night Shaun\" Shaun rips off his coat and tosses it away as he is dancing, only to have it tossed back. This is reminiscent of the scene in the 1980 movie ''[[Airplane!]]'', where [[Robert Hays]] tosses his white sport-coat away, only to have it tossed back in his face.\n* In \"Party Animals\", one of the sheep is dressed as a crude version of a [[Dalek]] trying to get up some stairs but failing because of the suit.\n* In \"Bitzer from the Black Lagoon\", Shaun cannot start the Farmer's truck and hits his head on the horn to get it started. This is a reference to ''[[Back to the Future]]''. \n* In \"Zebra Ducks of the Serengeti\", the Farmer's signpost over the gate falls over Bitzer - \u00e0 la Buster Keaton in ''[[Steamboat Bill, Jr.]]''\n* In \"An Ill Wind\", when the power supply to the farmhouse blows up, the Farmer grabs an axe and chops his wind turbine in a similar fashion to ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]''.\n* In \"Shaun Encounters\", two alien kids throw a bone for Bitzer. He catches the bone to ''[[Also sprach Zarathustra (Strauss)|Also sprach Zarathustra]]'' music. The scene is close related to the first scene with the apes in ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]''.\n* In \"Pig Trouble,\" the background music when the Farmer makes the pigs in charge of the flock is the song \"If I Had Words\". This is a reference to the movie ''[[Babe (film)|Babe]]'', which is about a pig becoming a sheep-herding pig.\n\n== Spin-off ==\n\n=== ''Timmy Time'' ===\n\n{{Main|Timmy Time}}\n\nIn 2009, [[Aardman Animations]] released [[Timmy Time]], a [[CBeebies]] [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] series aimed at preschoolers. It centres on Timmy's own adventures as he attends preschool for the first time and learns how to interact and play with a variety of young animal friends.<ref name=\"licensing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.licensing.biz/brand-profiles/39/Timmy|title=Timmy Tales|last=Loveday|first=Samantha|publisher=Licensing.biz|accessdate=23 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727083603/http://www.licensing.biz/brand-profiles/39/Timmy|archivedate=27 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n\n===Films===\n{{main|Shaun the Sheep Movie|A Shaun the Sheep Movie: Farmageddon}}\nAardman developed a feature film ''[[Shaun the Sheep Movie]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-bristol-12299286 | title=Aardman Animations plan new Shaun the Sheep film | publisher=BBC | date=27 January 2011 |accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> written and directed by Richard Starzak and [[Mark Burton (writer)|Mark Burton]], which was financed by French company [[StudioCanal]],<ref name=VarietySmashBenchmarks>{{cite news|last1=Hopewell|first1=John|title=\u2018Legend,\u2019 \u2018Shaun,\u2019 Smash Benchmarks for Studiocanal|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/legend-shaun-smash-benchmarks-as-studiocanal-universal-music-group-explore-synergies-exclusive-1201592926/|accessdate=15 September 2015|work=Variety|date=14 September 2015|archivedate= 15 September 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150915152410/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/legend-shaun-smash-benchmarks-as-studiocanal-universal-music-group-explore-synergies-exclusive-1201592926/ | url-status=live}}</ref> which was released on 6 February 2015. The film received very positive reviews from critics. Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 99% of critics have given the film a positive review.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaun the Sheep (2015)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shaun_the_sheep_2015/|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> The film opened to $3.2 million in the UK and grossed $22 millon in the UK and $106 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=shaunthesheep.htm|title=Shaun the Sheep Movie (2015) - Box Office Mojo|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October 2019, StudioCanal and Aardman produced a sequel titled ''[[A Shaun the Sheep Movie: Farmageddon]]''.<ref name=VarietySmashBenchmarks /><ref name=\"DeadlineReuniteFlock\">{{cite web|last1=Tartaglione|first1=Nancy|title=Aardman, Studiocanal Reunite Flock For \u2018Shaun The Sheep Movie 2\u2019 \u2013 AFM|url=https://deadline.com/2016/10/shaun-the-sheep-movie-2-aardman-studiocanal-afm-1201842166/|publisher=Deadline|accessdate=25 October 2016|date=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n{{Main|Shaun the Sheep (video game)}}\n\nOn 16 June 2008, [[D3 Publisher|D3 Publisher of America]], which had previously published a game based on Aardman's 2006 film ''[[Flushed Away]],'' announced that it would also release a video game based on Shaun's escapades. The ''Shaun the Sheep'' game was developed by [[Art Co., Ltd]] exclusively for [[Nintendo DS]], and was released in autumn 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=18932 | last1=Remo | first1=Chris | title = Q&A: D3 Talks New Coraline, Shaun The Sheep Deals, Strategy |accessdate = 16 June 2008 | date = 16 June 2008 |publisher = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref>\n\nA second game for [[Nintendo DS]], titled ''Shaun the Sheep: Off His Head'', was released on 23 October 2009, exclusively in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaun the Sheep: Off His Head|url=http://www.gamespot.com/shaun-the-sheep-off-his-head/|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Shaun the Sheep website is also home to several Flash-based games, including ''Home Sheep Home'',<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.shaunthesheep.com/games/homesheephome/ |title = Shaun the Sheep Flash game |publisher=Shaunt The Sheep |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130717091154/http://www.shaunthesheep.com/games/homesheephome |archivedate=17 July 2013 |accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> which was also made available at the iOS App Store for [[iPhone]], [[iPod touch]], and [[iPad]] in April 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/home-sheep-home/id433704428 |title = Home Sheep Home |publisher=iTunes |accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> A sequel, ''Home Sheep Home 2'', was released in December 2011 for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] PCs, [[iPhone]], [[iPod touch]], and [[iPad]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2011/12/aaardman-returns-with-updated-home-sheep-home-2-casual-game |title = Aaardman Returns With Updated Home Sheep Home 2 Casual Game |publisher=[[Gizmodo]] |author=Gary Cutlack |date=9 December 2011 |accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref> It was released on the [[Steam (software)|Steam]] digital distribution platform for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] PCs in February 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://store.steampowered.com/app/259810/Home_Sheep_Home_2 |title = Home Sheep Home 2 on Steam |publisher=[[Steam (software)|Steam]] |accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, an event course called ''Shaun's Mossy Mole Mischief'', was released on ''[[Super Mario Maker]]'', alongside with Shaun's costume.<ref>{{cite web|title=Costume Mario|url=http://www.mariowiki.com/Costume_Mario|publisher=Super Mario Wiki}}</ref>\n\nA movie adaptation of [[Shaun the sheep#video games|Home Sheep Home]] entitled ''Home Sheep Home: Farmageddon Party Edition'' was announced for release in October 2019 for [[Nintendo Switch]]. Shaun, Shirley and Timmy find their way back to the green grass of home. all hosted by Shaun\u2019s new alien pal Lu-La.<ref>https://shaunthesheep.com/news/home-sheep-home-farmageddon-party-edition-coming-soon</ref> The platform puzzle game will contain all the much loved gameplay from previous Home Sheep Home games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.homesheephomegame.com/|title=Home Sheep Home Farmageddon Party Edition game|first=Aardman Animations|last=Ltd|website=www.homesheephomegame.com}}</ref>\n\nA Shaun the Sheep game is planned for [[The Sandbox (video game)|The Sandbox]] voxel world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/sandbox-game/partnership-announcement-the-sandbox-ft-shaun-the-sheep-bf5ce6918375|title=Partnership Announcement: The Sandbox Ft. Shaun The Sheep|first=The|last=Sandbox|date=20 December 2019|website=Medium}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\nOn 9 March 2011, Shaun the Sheep made its live theatre d\u00e9but in ''Shaun's Big Show''.<ref>{{cite web | author=BWW News Desk | url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/uk-regional/article/SHAUNS-BIG-SHOW-Debuts-at-StokeonTrents-Regent-Theatre-Mar-9-13-20110222 | title=SHAUN'S BIG SHOW Debuts at Stoke-on-Trent's Regent Theatre, Mar. 9 -13 | publisher=BroadwayWorld.com | date=22 February 2011 | accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> The 100-minute-long musical/dance show features all the regular characters, including Bitzer, Shirley and Timmy.\n\nIn 2015, Shaun starred in [[Snow White|''Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs'']] [[pantomime]] at [[Bristol Hippodrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bristolpost.co.uk/star-Shaun-Sheep-joins-Bristol-panto-line/story-27947670-detail/story.html|title=A star is Shaun: Sheep joins Bristol panto line-up|date=8 October 2015|publisher=}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Shaun the Sheep Experience===\nIn 2015, a family attraction based on Shaun the Sheep, called \"The Shaun the Sheep Experience\" opened at [[Lands End]], rebranded \"Lamb's End\" for the duration of the attraction. It features original sets, models, and characters from many Aardman productions. Using green screen technology, guests are able to \"star\" in a scene from the show, as well as meet other characters from the Aardman filmography including [[Wallace and Gromit]] and [[Morph (animation)|Morph]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bennet|first1=Geoff|title=Bristol's Shaun the Sheep to be star of new family tourist attraction|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Shaun-Sheep-friends-star-Land-s-End-experience/story-23723823-detail/story.html|publisher=Bristol Post|accessdate=24 October 2015|date=29 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923231438/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Shaun-Sheep-friends-star-Land-s-End-experience/story-23723823-detail/story.html|archivedate=23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Promotional===\nOn 26 September 2013, the [[International Rugby Board]] and Aardman Animations announced that Shaun and other characters from the franchise would be used in a merchandising programme to promote the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]] to children.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/home/news/newsid=2068867.html#shaun+sheep+joins+rwc+2015+flock |title=Shaun the Sheep joins RWC 2015 flock |publisher=International Rugby Board |date=26 September 2013 |accessdate=26 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003042205/http://www.rugbyworldcup.com//home/news/newsid=2068867.html |archivedate=3 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Shaun the Sheep appeared as the face of the \"Holidays at Home are Great\" directive. In the advert, seeing the Farmer going away, Shaun and the flock decide to have their own holiday around the UK before the Farmer gets back.<ref>{{cite press release|title=VisitEngland teams up with Shaun the Sheep to promote holidays at home this year|url=https://www.visitengland.com/biz/media-centre/press-releases/2015/january-2015/visitengland-teams-shaun-sheep-promote-holidays-home-year|publisher=VisitEngland|accessdate=10 October 2015|date=14 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Shaun in the City===\n[[File:Shaun in the city London sculpture.jpg|thumb|Shaun in the City sculpture by [[Cath Kidston]], London|365x365px]]\nIn 2015, Shaun the Sheep starred in two public charity arts trails to raise money for sick children in hospitals across the UK. Organised by Wallace & Gromit's Children's Foundation in collaboration with Aardman, [[Shaun in the City]] saw 50 giant artist and celebrity-decorated sculptures of Shaun appear in London in the spring, before a further 70 appeared in Bristol throughout the summer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaun in the City|url=http://shauninthecity.org.uk/|publisher=Shaun in the City|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> All 120 sculptures were auctioned in October 2015, raising \u00a31,087,900 for [https://www.grandappeal.org.uk/ Wallace & Gromit's Grand Appeal] and [https://wallaceandgromitcharity.org/ Wallace & Gromit's Children's Charity].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaun in the City|url=http://www.visitlondon.com/things-to-do/event/41403646-shaun-in-the-city?ref=mosaic|publisher=Visit London|accessdate=24 October 2015|date=31 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172134/http://www.visitlondon.com/things-to-do/event/41403646-shaun-in-the-city?ref=mosaic|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Shaun the Sheep Land===\n[[File:Ram of the Match.jpg|thumb|353x353px|Shaun in the city sculpture <nowiki>''Ram of the match''</nowiki>]]\n\nA Shaun the Sheep theme park, titled ''Shaun the Sheep Land'' was opened at [[Sk\u00e5nes Djurpark]] in [[Sweden]] in early Summer 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Sk\u00e5ne Djurpark |url=http://www.skanesdjurpark.se/english/about-skaane-djurpark/ |accessdate=7 August 2016 |publisher=Sk\u00e5nes Djurpark}}</ref>\n\n== DVDs ==\n\n===Region 2 (UK)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!DVD name\n!# of episodes\n!Release date\n|-\n| Shaun the Sheep: Shape Up With Shaun (8 Baa...rilliant Adventures!)\n| 8\n| 12 September 2007; Re-Release: 23 July 2018\n|-\n| Shaun the Sheep: Off The Baa! (8 Woolly Adventures!)\n| 8\n| 12 November 2007; Re-Release: 23 July 2018\n|-\n| Shaun the Sheep: The Box Set! (Includes Shape Up With Shaun (8 Baa...rilliant Adventures!) and Off The Baa! (8 Woolly Adventures!) DVDs)\n| 16\n| 12 November 2007\n|-\n| Shaun the Sheep: Saturday Night Shaun (Fleece Is The Word!)\n| 8\n| 10 March 2008; Re-Release: 23 July 2018\n|-\n| Shaun the Sheep: Abracadabra\n| 8\n| 20 October 2008; Re-Release: 23 July 2018\n|-\n| Shaun the Sheep: Wash Day\n| 8\n| 17 November 2008; Re-Release: 23 July 2018\n|-\n| Shaun the Sheep: Triple Pack (Includes Saturday Night Shaun (Fleece Is The Word!), Abracadabr